00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:27.360
[Amit Varma]: Ashwin, welcome to the Scene and the Unseen.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:28.360
[Guest]: My pleasure. Absolutely.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:33.280
[Amit Varma]: Ashwin, tell me a little bit about your background because for someone who has both dabbled with

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:38.720
[Amit Varma]: politics and worked very hard in governance in recent years, you were trained for none

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:39.720
[Guest]: of these things.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:45.240
[Guest]: Well, I don't think you need to be trained for these things to participate in them. But

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:51.280
[Guest]: you're right. I wanted to be a physicist and an astronomer when I was young. And I guess

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:55.240
[Guest]: I was fortunate enough to go on to become something that I wanted to be when I was young,

00:03:55.240 --> 00:04:02.160
[Guest]: which is always a nice thing. But once I actually became an astronomer, it sort of dawned on

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:08.440
[Guest]: me that a lot of things that excited me were about observational astronomy. But many of

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:14.120
[Guest]: the programs that I sort of looked at for learning were more about astrophysics rather

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:20.000
[Guest]: than observational astronomy. And so I started thinking about what else I could do. And I

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.160
[Guest]: became interested in clouds and climate change.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.800
[Guest]: In the 90s in particular, all this stuff about sustainability and climate change was beginning

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:34.000
[Guest]: to come to the notice of a lot of people. And so I said I would study climate change.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.880
[Guest]: And in particular, I said I would study clouds and their impact on climate change. But I

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:44.480
[Guest]: also said I would study clouds in Antarctica and in the Arctic, polar clouds broadly, because

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:49.200
[Guest]: polar clouds have, in fact, potentially a much higher impact on climate change than

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:55.440
[Guest]: clouds anywhere else. And until the 1990s, many climate models did not even include data

00:04:55.440 --> 00:05:02.440
[Guest]: from above 60 North and below 60 South. So a lot of the data for climate modeling was

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:07.120
[Guest]: still being collected. And I was fortunate enough to go to one of those programs for

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:13.400
[Guest]: my doctoral work. And I spent 10 or 12 years looking at Antarctic clouds and Arctic clouds,

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:20.200
[Guest]: first from the ground and then from satellites at NASA. It was very much a lot of fun. I

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:24.600
[Guest]: sometimes miss that, and people ask me about that. But at some point, I just said I'm going

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:30.520
[Guest]: home. And a lot of people will say, why are you going home, leaving a job like this? I

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:33.440
[Guest]: can only say that if I'd gone to Calcutta and come back, nobody would say, why are you

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:37.520
[Guest]: going home? Or if I'd gone to Delhi and come back, nobody would say that. I suppose people

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:42.840
[Guest]: think that if you go to Washington, you're less likely to come home. But anyway, having

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:49.720
[Guest]: made that decision, I came back. And there weren't any Antarctic clouds to study here.

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:55.040
[Guest]: So I had to find something else to do. A few people that I spoke to at that time, I'd already

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:00.560
[Guest]: begun to be interested in public interest media and communication by then. And by talking

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:06.200
[Guest]: to a few people, I got the sense that one of the things I could look at was how cities

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:13.000
[Guest]: are shaping up in India. Urbanization is a big part of what is going on in the country.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:19.200
[Guest]: And it's not really well-guided even today. And so I began to look at that and see what

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:24.440
[Guest]: is it that I could contribute as a person not coming from the right quote-unquote background

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:32.400
[Guest]: for this. And it occurred to me that one thing I could do was help visualize the city better.

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:38.360
[Guest]: A lot of problems that we try to solve, we're trying to solve them without actually being

00:06:38.360 --> 00:06:44.520
[Guest]: able to see the problem. People will talk about bad traffic and poor water supply and

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:49.080
[Guest]: lack of housing and all that. But if you ask them to give a spatial description of those

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:54.800
[Guest]: problems, not a lot of people know this, even in the agencies that are tasked with solving

00:06:54.800 --> 00:07:01.800
[Guest]: them. So I said, let's start to put together these visualizations of cities and bring together

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:05.800
[Guest]: related things. There are two reasons to do that. One is to enable understanding through

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:13.840
[Guest]: visualization. The second is to enable just integration. All the departments work in silos.

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:18.800
[Guest]: So the bus company has its data. Metro has its data. Everybody has their own data. They

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:23.120
[Guest]: don't really work together. So to be able to pull them, whereas as a citizen, what you

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:27.840
[Guest]: care about is mobility in the city. You don't really care about these silos. So could you

00:07:27.840 --> 00:07:32.360
[Guest]: bring them together becomes the question. And I said, that's another reason to start

00:07:32.360 --> 00:07:38.240
[Guest]: working on visualizations as well. And that's what I started doing. And from there, all

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:41.920
[Guest]: sorts of things began to happen in urban governance.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:47.320
[Amit Varma]: And is there therefore taking off from that a case to be made that interdisciplinary pollination

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:52.200
[Amit Varma]: is very important for good decision making? Because part of the reason I guess you were

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:57.600
[Amit Varma]: able to think of cities in this way that let's visualize especially is because of your prior

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:02.240
[Amit Varma]: training and experience in completely unrelated fields. Is that something that you think is

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:08.720
[Amit Varma]: important and is a homogenization of whatever experience or training that people traditionally

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:11.200
[Amit Varma]: bring into these fields a problem?

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:16.320
[Guest]: I'm not sure, but certainly there are multiple axes on which you need to look at the problem.

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:20.840
[Guest]: I always say that working with your municipal corporation is harder than working at NASA

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:27.560
[Guest]: for a variety of reasons. But there are four axes on which you need to look for intersections.

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:36.520
[Guest]: One is topical across many topics. What can you bring together? The second is scale. How

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:40.320
[Guest]: do you think of the city at one scale? How do you think of neighborhoods at one scale?

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:49.240
[Guest]: You know, streets and blocks and all of that. That's the second axis. The third axis is

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:56.880
[Guest]: stakeholder. Typically, Sarkar has its way of imagining the city. The citizens have their

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:01.280
[Guest]: way of knowing their neighborhoods and imagining the city. And businesses have a different

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:06.920
[Guest]: way of imagining the city. But the city actually is at the intersection of all of these things.

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:11.200
[Guest]: It's both complementary and supplementary intersections of all of these things. So that's

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:15.960
[Guest]: the third axis. And the fourth is learning from each other. What have other cities done

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:23.480
[Guest]: in similar situations? And so if we learn from these four axes simultaneously, then

00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:32.640
[Guest]: anyone can do it. It's not so much about interdisciplinarity as it is about the intersections of these

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:33.880
[Amit Varma]: four axes.

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:37.840
[Amit Varma]: So it's more what you focus on than what you have been trained to focus on.

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:43.040
[Guest]: Correct. You work backwards from the problem, right? You don't work forwards alone. Because

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:48.120
[Guest]: when you do this forwards alone, you end up with this Sarkar way of doing things. Sarkar

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:53.960
[Guest]: does a lot of inputs. You go to any government department and say, this should be done. And

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:59.560
[Guest]: inevitably, a lot of them will tell you it's happening, it's being done. And that may even

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:05.560
[Guest]: be true. But if you look at how fast it's being done, you're not going to get a good

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:09.320
[Guest]: sense that it can ever get done well enough or quickly enough to solve the problem that's

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:14.520
[Guest]: being described. So it's much better to work backwards from the problem, right? It's much

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:18.720
[Guest]: better to say there's a housing deficit. How big is the housing deficit? How are you going

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:24.000
[Guest]: to fix that deficit? Rather than saying it's the responsibility of the development authority

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
[Guest]: to create housing. How do we create housing? How much housing do we create? So these are

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:33.080
[Guest]: very different approaches to public problem solving. And public problem solving is a sort

00:10:33.080 --> 00:10:38.240
[Guest]: of a complex thing. I described this. A public problem is something about which everyone

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:42.720
[Guest]: agrees that something should be done. But the minute you propose something, one set

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:47.120
[Guest]: of people say, this is not the thing that should be done. Right? So you've got to work

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:52.720
[Guest]: through that a lot. And that's why it's important to keep your eyes on the problem and work

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:57.160
[Amit Varma]: backwards from that. Right. And, you know, later in the episode, in the second half of

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:01.360
[Amit Varma]: the episode, you know, I have a lot else to ask you about urban governance and cities

00:11:01.360 --> 00:11:06.280
[Amit Varma]: and traffic and so on areas that you're deeply insightful in. But to just sort of go back

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:11.920
[Amit Varma]: to biography for a moment, I'm also very interested in what kind of books you read as a young

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:16.920
[Amit Varma]: person. Like what were the formative influences on you? Who were your intellectual heroes

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:18.920
[Amit Varma]: growing up and as a young adult?

00:11:18.920 --> 00:11:27.320
[Guest]: Well, I was fascinated by polymaths. You know, I like people like Da Vinci, Russell, Aristotle.

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:33.160
[Guest]: You sort of have this notion that people become successful in one thing. But there are also

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:37.640
[Guest]: these exceptional people who did many things in life and did them all well. It's not like

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:41.560
[Guest]: they were primarily one thing and did a few other things. Everything that did, they did

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:46.560
[Guest]: really well. And I kind of found that fascinating. So I started thinking about how do you do

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:51.840
[Guest]: many things, right? Like I was talking in a school a few days ago and said, a lot of

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:55.880
[Guest]: young people are asked, what do you want to be when you grow up? The implication is that

00:11:55.880 --> 00:12:00.080
[Guest]: there's one answer to that question. I think you should ask, what all do you want to be

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:06.120
[Guest]: when you grow up? And then you would get a very different set of answers. But by and

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:10.560
[Guest]: large, you know, I'm not that different in terms of what I read or saw. I read the newspaper,

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:18.520
[Guest]: of course, like all kids. I read comics and novels that interest young children. But I

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:23.120
[Guest]: also read a lot of stuff that was just information gathering and knowledge development. And at

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:26.120
[Guest]: some point, I made it a deliberate thing to say that every day I'm going to read a few

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:31.560
[Guest]: minutes at least of stuff that informs and educates me. I've got this whole rhythm for

00:12:31.560 --> 00:12:36.960
[Guest]: living, which I think contributes to a learning environment automatically. And it's something

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.880
[Guest]: I even tell a lot of young people about. It's called the seven four-letter words of living

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest]: well. We can talk about that later if you want.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.080
[Amit Varma]: But let's talk about it now because I'm very curious to sort of reform my working habits.

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:55.680
[Guest]: So I, over the years, more empirically than more by incidental discovery, rather than

00:12:55.680 --> 00:13:05.000
[Guest]: as a theory, I've come up with seven four-letter words that if you live like this, you can

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:11.880
[Guest]: be very successful and very happy and live a very sort of enriching life, which sort

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:18.240
[Guest]: of achieves some things too. And you only need to do this for 10 minutes a day. And

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:21.160
[Guest]: you can do any one of them for 10 minutes a day. So it's actually very easy.

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:22.160
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to do all seven.

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:27.320
[Guest]: No, no. You can do any one of them for 10 minutes a day. So in all seven, there's a

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:37.360
[Guest]: catch and then there's an overall catch. Okay. So the first one is make. You have to make

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:42.360
[Guest]: something yourself. You have to make it with your hands. You can make even a computer program.

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:45.200
[Guest]: It doesn't have to be a physical object, but you have to make it.

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:47.200
[Guest]: Can you write something? Is that allowed?

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:51.600
[Guest]: Yeah. You, whatever you do. I suppose sort of everyone's looking for the thing that they

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:56.600
[Guest]: can do really well, maybe. But yeah, it can be anything. It can be a chair. It can be

00:13:56.600 --> 00:14:01.080
[Guest]: a pot. It can be a computer program. It can be an article that you're writing. All of

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:10.680
[Guest]: this is okay, but you have to do it yourself. The second one is meet, right? Meet essentially

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:16.120
[Guest]: means meet people, but there's a catch. Again, like I said, all seven things have a catch.

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:24.640
[Guest]: In meet, the catch is only strangers count. People that you know don't count. And it's

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:29.920
[Guest]: even better if you're making a deliberate effort to meet them rather than saying I incidentally

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:37.040
[Guest]: met these people. And the reason this helps is that strangers broaden your perspective

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:40.760
[Guest]: of things. They have vantage points that are different from yours. So that's the second

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:46.400
[Guest]: one. The third one is read, right? And you asked about reading earlier. So it's one of

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:55.360
[Guest]: the habits. Comics don't count. Even newspapers don't count for me anymore. Only things that

00:14:55.360 --> 00:15:00.760
[Guest]: inform and educate you count. You can decide what informs and educates you and how you're

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:06.240
[Guest]: going to pursue a strategy of reading and learning within that framework. So that's

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:12.480
[Guest]: the third one, read. And keep in mind, 10 minutes is enough. Any one of this is enough.

00:15:12.480 --> 00:15:16.440
[Guest]: I don't recommend that you do only one of them all the time. That reading all the time

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:20.800
[Guest]: doesn't make any sense. But at least three or four, you must do.

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:26.920
[Guest]: The fourth one is kind of like a guy's thing because it's cook. And what I really mean

00:15:26.920 --> 00:15:32.520
[Guest]: by cook is do something that you think is normally someone else's job. You think it's

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:37.080
[Guest]: mom's job, it's the wife's job, somebody. But really all I'm doing is using it as a

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:43.280
[Guest]: metaphor for saying, do something that I normally think is not my job, but somebody else's job.

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:46.640
[Guest]: So you get into someone else's skin and that builds empathy and so on.

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:54.360
[Guest]: Sort of. No, no. I'm not trying to do it for a reason. I'm just saying, if you did this,

00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:59.040
[Guest]: all sorts of things would happen as a result of it. And it could be anything else. If you

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:03.640
[Guest]: already anyway cook, find something else that is stuff that you'd normally expect somebody

00:16:03.640 --> 00:16:07.320
[Guest]: else to do. Maybe you can mop the house. I don't know what it is, but you can figure

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:15.600
[Guest]: out something that isn't your job normally. The fifth one is play. Playing solitaire on

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:24.560
[Guest]: your computer doesn't count. I really mean team sports. I suppose doubles in table tennis

00:16:24.560 --> 00:16:29.960
[Guest]: or tennis is all right, but ideally team sports. Playing online chess doesn't count. No, no.

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:36.240
[Guest]: Contact sports is better than sort of non-contact sports. And play is easier for kids, especially

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:40.920
[Guest]: because they're in school, they play. So when I tell this in schools, I change it a little

00:16:40.920 --> 00:16:48.760
[Guest]: bit. Play, but not with someone in your school or someone in your community. Find a way of

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:53.760
[Guest]: playing with somebody who you don't normally come into contact with. So it's a little bit

00:16:53.760 --> 00:17:00.400
[Guest]: of nuance for certain groups. How many have we done? Five. Okay. Then the sixth one is

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:06.520
[Guest]: vote. And by vote, I don't really mean go and press a button on election day, although

00:17:06.520 --> 00:17:12.640
[Guest]: you could do that too. I really mean vote as a way of supporting other people. To be

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:18.480
[Guest]: able to stand up and say, I support this, this thing that someone is doing or this person

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:23.800
[Guest]: in some way. And I think it's important because it helps us to celebrate other people. It

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:29.040
[Guest]: helps us to take a stand, stand on what it is that we care about. It clarifies our own

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:35.480
[Guest]: thinking to ourselves, all of that stuff. So vote is the sixth one. What did I go through?

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:40.160
[Amit Varma]: We've done make, meet, read, cook, play, vote.

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:45.200
[Guest]: Give is the last one, right? And again, give doesn't mean give something to your sister

00:17:45.200 --> 00:17:50.600
[Guest]: or your cousin, not to your friends. You have to give to someone in need, right? It can

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:54.080
[Guest]: be anything. You can give them money. If you have money, you can give them a little of

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:58.920
[Guest]: your time. You can volunteer. You can do whatever it is. You have to give. The thing that you

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:03.600
[Guest]: give must be yours to give. So you can't give other people's stuff away and that doesn't

00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:11.640
[Guest]: count. And it must genuinely be to someone who needs it, not just wants it or would like

00:18:11.640 --> 00:18:17.640
[Guest]: to have it. So these are the seven things. And there's another catch. You can't miss

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:24.760
[Guest]: a day, right? And that's a very important catch. If you miss a day, it's as bad as missing

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:31.240
[Guest]: a year, right? And it takes a while to realize that missing a day is as bad as missing a

00:18:31.240 --> 00:18:36.520
[Guest]: year because a lot of people say, how can missing a day be as bad as missing a year?

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:40.280
[Guest]: It's because, I mean, you can miss for health reasons and stuff like that. I don't think

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:47.640
[Guest]: that I wouldn't begrudge myself that. But if I miss because I'm not doing it, then it's

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:53.920
[Guest]: not me. So I would say, then I'm going to start again and be more deliberate about it.

00:18:53.920 --> 00:19:00.720
[Guest]: The idea in my mind was to get this to a point where I can be sure I'm doing one or more

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:07.760
[Guest]: of these every day for a few minutes without needing to think about it. I'm pretty sure

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:12.920
[Guest]: I'll do at least two or three of this every day for 10 minutes. And the reason I'm sure

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:18.520
[Guest]: of that is that there's a rhythm of how you live, which incidentally makes time for one

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:24.160
[Guest]: or more of these things. So, and I've said this to a lot of young people. I've said this

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:30.080
[Guest]: to a few others in schools and colleges and even some older people and encourage some

00:19:30.080 --> 00:19:35.200
[Guest]: of them to try it. A lot of people have come back and said, you know what, it really works.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:39.080
[Guest]: And I don't know why it works to tell you the truth. I'm not a sort of a theorist about

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:44.640
[Guest]: these things. I think it works because it broadens your mind. It brings you in contact

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:51.640
[Guest]: with a lot of different people. It sort of gets you out of your comfort zone in the ways

00:19:51.640 --> 00:19:56.280
[Guest]: in which you would approach things. And it builds rhythm. I think rhythm is the biggest

00:19:56.280 --> 00:19:57.280
[Guest]: thing that you can build.

00:19:57.280 --> 00:20:01.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's fantastic. I'll take some time to process this. As you went through the list,

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:06.240
[Amit Varma]: I thought, okay, the one thing that's a problem for me here is play contact sports, because

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:11.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of a solitary person and don't go out much to meet people. And I can easily,

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:16.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, read every day. I mean, I do read every day, but I set myself the sort of my

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:21.720
[Amit Varma]: personal target is like 20 books a month at least. So I do end up doing that. So I could

00:20:21.720 --> 00:20:26.520
[Amit Varma]: easily cheat by saying I read every day, I haven't missed a single day. But I guess one

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:31.360
[Guest]: has to, you know, do all seven of them in a particular way.

00:20:31.360 --> 00:20:35.800
[Guest]: I think it's possible that at different stages in your life, you can't do all seven. I think

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:41.480
[Guest]: we have to accept that. But I'm saying this works well. And there have been times when

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:47.920
[Guest]: I'll go long periods without doing one or the other. But the key is to get to a point

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:53.400
[Guest]: where you're doing at least one of them every day. And there's some diversity within that,

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:57.120
[Guest]: so that you're not doing the same thing or the same two things. But, you know, you can

00:20:57.120 --> 00:21:01.960
[Guest]: do five of them. Each week, if you do five of them, you're pretty much there. It doesn't

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:07.080
[Guest]: have to be all seven. It's nice if it's all seven, because some of them do require a stretch

00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:11.200
[Guest]: at some level. But five is not bad.

00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:14.600
[Amit Varma]: Great food for thought. And I would recommend you write a self-help book at some point,

00:21:14.600 --> 00:21:19.040
[Amit Varma]: except that I think there are other books the nation needs you to write before that.

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:25.360
[Guest]: I've been writing a book for almost six years now. And maybe that's a good segue, because

00:21:25.360 --> 00:21:35.440
[Guest]: it's a segue into a lot of things I do. Well, tentatively, I've called it The Good Indian.

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:43.480
[Guest]: And it's a history of thinking about this phrase, who is a good Indian? And broadly,

00:21:43.480 --> 00:21:53.800
[Guest]: in my mind, it's from 1905-1910 to 2005-2010. And you could say it's from Gokhale to Arnab.

00:21:53.800 --> 00:21:59.800
[Guest]: And then, therefore, it's from Gandhiji's mentor to Gandhiji's disciple in some way.

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:07.040
[Guest]: And there's a narrative that I've built for this. I mean, I'm still sort of exploring

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:12.680
[Guest]: and developing pieces of it. But broadly, let me put it to you like this. In the early

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:18.160
[Guest]: part of the last century, it was pretty clear who was a good Indian. If you wanted the British

00:22:18.160 --> 00:22:22.800
[Guest]: to get out of India, and you were doing something to make that happen, you were a good Indian.

00:22:22.800 --> 00:22:26.240
[Amit Varma]: But is that clear in retrospect? Like, at the time, the British would have looked at

00:22:26.240 --> 00:22:27.240
[Amit Varma]: it differently?

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:30.680
[Guest]: No, no. I'm saying this is a question if you ask yourself as an Indian.

00:22:30.680 --> 00:22:31.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, today.

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:38.600
[Guest]: Okay. Of course, there are all kinds of views that others can take about it. But I'm saying,

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:43.560
[Guest]: if you, in your own society, in your own family, in your own community, whatever, however you

00:22:43.560 --> 00:22:48.480
[Guest]: see it, if you'd ask this question, who's a good Indian? A lot of the answer would have

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:56.160
[Guest]: revolved around the idea of self-rule. And I make a distinction between independence

00:22:56.160 --> 00:22:59.800
[Guest]: and self-rule. And we should talk about that as well. I think a lot of the freedom movement

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:05.960
[Guest]: was actually about self-rule rather than liberty and independence. And that has shaped a lot

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:11.920
[Guest]: of our governance since then as well. But to come back to this story, it was very clear.

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:16.320
[Guest]: You fought for self-rule or independence or freedom, and you were a good Indian because

00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:22.960
[Guest]: you did that. Then in 1947, the British went away. And so that was not a good enough, that

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:29.320
[Guest]: was not a useful answer to the question, who is a good Indian? So you now needed something

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:36.160
[Guest]: else. And Nehru kind of stepped into that reach, as it were, and gave you a suggestion.

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:42.760
[Guest]: He said, the state will build India. And if you are part of the state building India,

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:48.600
[Guest]: or if you applaud the state building India, you're a good Indian. You can either be in

00:23:48.600 --> 00:23:54.120
[Guest]: the services or you respect and applaud Sarkar and the services. And that's what it means

00:23:54.120 --> 00:24:00.840
[Guest]: to be a good Indian, that this tryst with destiny, in his mind was really Sarkar's tryst

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:05.840
[Guest]: with destiny. I don't think he ever saw it as the society's tryst with destiny or even

00:24:05.840 --> 00:24:12.400
[Guest]: industry's tryst with destiny. And so we went on with that for, I'm going to say, 20 years

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:19.960
[Guest]: or so. And without connecting it too much to the emergency question itself, what happened

00:24:19.960 --> 00:24:26.720
[Guest]: by the late 70s, mid to late 70s, early 80s, is that a lot of people began to say, very

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:32.440
[Guest]: good, the state is developing India. But in the meantime, you haven't been delivering

00:24:32.440 --> 00:24:40.520
[Guest]: our needs, you haven't been delivering the essentials of a development framework. Can

00:24:40.520 --> 00:24:45.800
[Guest]: you please deliver that? And then get on with your job of building India, even if you feel

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:50.600
[Guest]: that the country should be state-led. And by Indira Gandhi's time, the notion that the

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:55.120
[Guest]: country should be state-led had taken even stronger form with nationalization and a bunch

00:24:55.120 --> 00:25:03.720
[Guest]: of other things. And so when this question came up, there was a kind of a fudgy answer

00:25:03.720 --> 00:25:09.320
[Guest]: to it. And the fudgy answer was, state is not malevolent. It still means to do good.

00:25:09.320 --> 00:25:17.000
[Guest]: It's still the appropriate vehicle for leading development in India, but it's simply overburdened

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:23.120
[Guest]: and it lacks the capacity to deliver all these good things. And therefore, we need an intermediate

00:25:23.120 --> 00:25:31.640
[Guest]: class to deliver those good things. And that class was the NGO. So you had this massive

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:39.600
[Guest]: upsurge of civic, civil society and community action through non-governmental organizations,

00:25:39.600 --> 00:25:45.760
[Guest]: many of whom are loosely sort of allied to someone or the other in the state space as

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:52.080
[Guest]: well. But they began to see themselves as intermediaries. The state can't do everything.

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:56.920
[Guest]: So on behalf of the state, we'll do a bunch of things for you. And this sort of came to

00:25:56.920 --> 00:26:05.280
[Guest]: a culmination, if you will, I'm going to say in UPA too, probably, with the National Advisory

00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:13.680
[Guest]: Council itself being dominated by civil society members to the point that it was effectively

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:19.600
[Guest]: a supracabinet of sorts. And I have many friends who were on it, so I know what I'm saying

00:26:19.600 --> 00:26:24.100
[Guest]: about this. And you could see that as a good thing or a bad thing, but it was basically

00:26:24.100 --> 00:26:32.360
[Guest]: a different kind of intermediation and representation that brought people there. The typical NGO,

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:39.440
[Guest]: however, had a certain kind of intermediation that was going on. The country was historically

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:45.400
[Guest]: very rural. NGOs tended by and large to be urban or the NGO leaders tended to be by and

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:51.600
[Guest]: large urban. And that was kind of an interesting thing as well. And you can look at even, oh,

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:57.520
[Guest]: I don't know, an MKSS might be a good example of something that was kind of clearly starting

00:26:57.520 --> 00:27:06.920
[Guest]: from rural deprivation, rural misgovernance, and articulating ideas about how information,

00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:12.360
[Guest]: employment and all of these things should be better delivered and protected in rural

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:20.040
[Guest]: settings. But a lot of the leadership for that, the spokesmanship for that is urban.

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:27.560
[Guest]: I'm sure you can find more examples of that. In the NGO sector, there was a lot of that.

00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:37.480
[Guest]: Urban representation of rural poverty alleviation. But after a while, I think that... And so

00:27:37.480 --> 00:27:42.360
[Guest]: if you were in the NGO sector, if you were in civil society, if you were enabling this

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:47.080
[Guest]: development outcome as a partner of the state, not as an opponent of this, but as a partner

00:27:47.080 --> 00:27:51.880
[Guest]: of... Then you were a good Indian, right? So it's a widening class of good Indians.

00:27:51.880 --> 00:27:55.200
[Guest]: Initially you were a good Indian if you were in the state or applauding the state. Now

00:27:55.200 --> 00:28:00.880
[Guest]: if you're in the state, applauding the state, or with the state, you're a good Indian. But

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:05.680
[Guest]: then what happened? Urbanization started to pick up in a massive way. And after a while,

00:28:05.680 --> 00:28:11.040
[Guest]: it became clear, even to end beneficiaries and citizens, that really there's an element

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:17.440
[Guest]: of geographical separation, which is the reason they need intermediation. Without the geographical

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:22.920
[Guest]: separation, they can directly approach the powers, the corridors of power. And in places

00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:29.680
[Guest]: like Delhi or Bangalore, this is quite obvious. I can see Vidhan Sardar from my house, right?

00:28:29.680 --> 00:28:34.000
[Guest]: Not I personally, but for those who can see Vidhan Sardar from their house, the notion

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:39.280
[Guest]: that they need intermediation from anybody, or I can see my corporation office, or I can

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:45.840
[Guest]: see whatever. There's a lot of the Sarkar that is visible from where I live. So urbanization

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:53.800
[Guest]: made people feel proximate enough to the Sarkar to start thinking they did not need intermediation.

00:28:53.800 --> 00:29:03.760
[Guest]: And this is where the idea of decentralization and loosely, a poorly understood idea of Swaraj

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:11.360
[Guest]: began to sort of appear on the street, in terms of a demand to be included in governance

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:16.080
[Guest]: rather than merely represented in government. It was not so much representative democracy

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:20.800
[Guest]: anymore that people wanted. They said, I want to participate in this process myself. I don't

00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:26.920
[Guest]: want intermediation. And I'm not satisfied with only representation. And it became government

00:29:26.920 --> 00:29:33.800
[Guest]: by the people in some way. And if you look at it, by the time India against corruption

00:29:33.800 --> 00:29:40.360
[Guest]: happened, that was actually the dominant demand, right? It was vaguely articulated and maybe

00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:45.480
[Guest]: even poorly represented by different sets of people saying different things in that

00:29:45.480 --> 00:29:51.160
[Guest]: meaning. But the idea was again and again, the same thing. We're tired of you. We're

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:58.400
[Guest]: tired of merely people who we elect, but don't have any subsequent control over. The local

00:29:58.400 --> 00:30:03.160
[Guest]: thing was a way of saying one kind of control is to yank you back. But really, that's the

00:30:03.160 --> 00:30:08.600
[Guest]: outlier, if you ask me. That's not really the goal of any democratic process. It's sort

00:30:08.600 --> 00:30:12.120
[Guest]: of almost a check and balance at best. So the real goal is to be able to say after they

00:30:12.120 --> 00:30:16.720
[Guest]: elect somebody, how do I begin to be able to engage with that thing in a much better

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:21.480
[Guest]: way? Or can I have a system in which the guy who gets elected is also a guy who's been

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:31.120
[Guest]: selected in some way in society previously? And this government by the people, Swaraj,

00:30:31.120 --> 00:30:35.800
[Guest]: and decentralization as imagined in the 73rd and 74th amendments. So all of those began

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:41.260
[Guest]: to converge in this expectation that today people want to participate directly themselves

00:30:41.260 --> 00:30:47.520
[Guest]: in deciding some of the destinies that they encounter through. And now if you are a participant

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:52.440
[Guest]: in that process, you're a good Indian. It doesn't mean there's a thing, and it could

00:30:52.440 --> 00:30:55.720
[Guest]: be for any agenda. It could be for an agenda of nationalism. It could be for an agenda

00:30:55.720 --> 00:31:00.400
[Guest]: of something else, regionalism, federalism. But ultimately, I think we're coming much

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:08.360
[Guest]: more strongly to the idea that participatory citizenship is what earns the label of good

00:31:08.360 --> 00:31:17.480
[Guest]: Indianness. And so I see this as the sweep that has happened over the last 100 years.

00:31:17.480 --> 00:31:22.320
[Guest]: And how much it sticks, we'll have to see. But a lot of what we're seeing in politics

00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:32.360
[Guest]: now is a demand for inclusion in decision making, is a demand for saying, I'm tired

00:31:32.360 --> 00:31:35.520
[Guest]: of other people making all these decisions for me.

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:40.480
[Amit Varma]: That's kind of fascinating. There's a lot to unpack in that. And one of the first things

00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:46.640
[Amit Varma]: that strikes me, obviously, is that if I look at this historical sweep, you've described

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:53.600
[Amit Varma]: as especially post-independence from an economic lens, then I am thinking of incentives, that

00:31:53.600 --> 00:31:58.200
[Amit Varma]: I'm looking at the incentives of the state, the people who sort of man the state, the

00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:02.320
[Amit Varma]: politicians and the bureaucrats and so on, and what their incentives are. And that doesn't

00:32:02.320 --> 00:32:08.800
[Amit Varma]: necessarily move towards a national interest. It do for NGOs, who then once they form their

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:14.320
[Amit Varma]: NGOs and start getting funding from wherever they do have different sets of overlapping

00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:19.840
[Amit Varma]: incentives, which might divert them from the original purpose like the state itself. And

00:32:19.840 --> 00:32:26.160
[Amit Varma]: now you're speaking of participatory democracy. And here, what sort of strikes me is that

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:33.040
[Amit Varma]: I want to ask you about incentives in two contexts. One context is the incentive of

00:32:33.040 --> 00:32:39.800
[Amit Varma]: the citizen to participate. Because my sense always as a citizen is, and I'm not saying

00:32:39.800 --> 00:32:45.440
[Amit Varma]: my but you know, an individual citizens take would typically be that my one vote doesn't

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:51.240
[Amit Varma]: make a difference. My participation doesn't make a difference. Why should I participate?

00:32:51.240 --> 00:32:56.600
[Amit Varma]: And why should I even keep myself informed about things that matter what public choice

00:32:56.600 --> 00:33:02.800
[Amit Varma]: is called rational ignorance. And the other set of incentives is that our government simply

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:07.920
[Amit Varma]: isn't local enough, which is, of course, something you've been writing about for many years that

00:33:07.920 --> 00:33:11.600
[Amit Varma]: our governments are too centralized. And at the local urban governance level, there is

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:17.120
[Amit Varma]: a massive disconnect between power and accountability. The people who care for my vote don't actually

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:24.040
[Amit Varma]: have the power to change my life, and vice versa. Yes, no, I, I have some experience

00:33:24.040 --> 00:33:28.720
[Guest]: with this. And of course, nowadays, people sort of explain it in a certain way. But you

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:34.940
[Guest]: have to sort of keep in mind that when I started to do what I now call public problem solving

00:33:34.940 --> 00:33:40.000
[Guest]: on the ground, I was like anybody else, a quote, unquote, nobody, right? The system

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:44.000
[Guest]: doesn't know you, you're, you might be well educated and all of that, the system doesn't

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:49.840
[Guest]: really know you. And that's not a bad beginning, because it's sort of whatever beginning you

00:33:49.840 --> 00:33:56.080
[Guest]: make from there, in theory is replicable by a lot of other people. So in my mind, it began

00:33:56.080 --> 00:34:04.320
[Guest]: like this. I live in Kepinagar, in Adikeri. And next to my community, apartment community,

00:34:04.320 --> 00:34:10.480
[Guest]: there's a lake. I did. And normally, if you bought a house, even a flat, and there was

00:34:10.480 --> 00:34:16.720
[Guest]: a lake next to it, the guy selling it would advertise it, saying there's a lot of money

00:34:16.720 --> 00:34:22.640
[Guest]: to be made by advertising the lakefront community. But the guy I bought the flat from didn't

00:34:22.640 --> 00:34:27.120
[Guest]: even mention it. And once you look at it, you sort of realized why it wasn't really

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:31.480
[Guest]: a lake, it was sort of a sewage pit of some kind, various kinds of things had gathered

00:34:31.480 --> 00:34:37.560
[Guest]: in it, sort of had some historical resemblance to a lake. But apart from that, it was nothing

00:34:37.560 --> 00:34:44.880
[Guest]: like a lake. And so some people in the neighborhood began to say, let's just clean it. All right,

00:34:44.880 --> 00:34:50.200
[Guest]: I'm sure there's somebody in charge of cleaning it, but let's clean it. And so we began to

00:34:50.200 --> 00:34:57.520
[Guest]: do that. And along came somebody from the municipality to say, who the hell are you?

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:04.120
[Guest]: And what are you doing? So we said, okay, well, who are you? And he said, I'm the chief

00:35:04.120 --> 00:35:10.640
[Guest]: engineer for lakes. So we asked him, what do you do? Clearly, this is a lake, you're

00:35:10.640 --> 00:35:14.400
[Guest]: the chief engineer for lakes, so this is the condition of the lake. So it's fair for me

00:35:14.400 --> 00:35:21.320
[Guest]: to ask, what do you do? And he sort of immediately was a little bit defensive about that. He

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:25.720
[Guest]: said, you don't understand, we have so many lakes, the budget is so small. You know, there's

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:32.840
[Guest]: like all kinds of things that are obstacles to doing this. But he was also good enough,

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:38.480
[Guest]: his name was Satish, he was a reasonable officer. He sort of was good enough to admit that on

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:44.040
[Guest]: their own, the municipality couldn't really crack this problem. And so I sort of pushed

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:52.600
[Guest]: the municipality to be a little more open-minded about saying, we'll manage the lake. And initially,

00:35:52.600 --> 00:35:57.680
[Guest]: the response was a little bit confused. People would say, well, normally people ask to manage

00:35:57.680 --> 00:36:03.280
[Guest]: parks and playgrounds. Nobody's actually asked to manage a lake. It's kind of a significant

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:08.200
[Guest]: thing. So that's all right. But you know, you say to yourself, we'll manage what we

00:36:08.200 --> 00:36:13.680
[Guest]: can and you do the rest that really requires government level action. Infrastructure spending,

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:19.480
[Guest]: maybe some staffing costs, whatever it is. But by and large, the notion that people could

00:36:19.480 --> 00:36:25.320
[Guest]: manage the community spaces, so it began to sort of... And because you see an example

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:31.560
[Guest]: like that and you tell yourself, this addition of people is the addition of capacity. First,

00:36:31.560 --> 00:36:35.800
[Guest]: we have to see that the addition of people is the addition of capacity. In India, unfortunately,

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:40.440
[Guest]: we tend to see population as the problem. We tend to count the people without counting

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:45.560
[Guest]: their worth. We think those cities are overcrowded. Overcrowded is great, you have so many people

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:50.640
[Guest]: to do stuff. But most people look at overcrowded and they think, oh my God, there are so many

00:36:50.640 --> 00:36:54.800
[Guest]: people for whom I have to do stuff. That's not necessary. But the critical thing that

00:36:54.800 --> 00:37:00.040
[Guest]: happened after the Puttanallee Lake revival, and it's a sort of a well-chronicled story

00:37:00.040 --> 00:37:07.120
[Guest]: by now, was I was then, by then sort of beginning to do a few things in Sarkar also. So I pushed

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:12.600
[Guest]: BBMP into an MOU-type arrangement between the local community and the municipality to

00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:18.120
[Guest]: say that this kind of stewardship of a public space is good. And with certain conditions,

00:37:18.120 --> 00:37:23.480
[Guest]: no commercialization. In those days, there'd be no phishing, some various kinds of things.

00:37:23.480 --> 00:37:28.960
[Guest]: But those kinds of things, the community, a local group, a local trust in the community

00:37:28.960 --> 00:37:33.880
[Guest]: could have stewardship of the lake. And I was also sensible enough to keep myself out

00:37:33.880 --> 00:37:40.800
[Guest]: of it, not to get into any conflicts of interest and all of that. But more critically, what

00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:48.480
[Guest]: also happened is we took that document, this MOU, and went around to other lake communities,

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:52.520
[Guest]: people who lived near some lake or the other. And so we've got one of these, almost like

00:37:52.520 --> 00:37:57.640
[Guest]: a child bragging about chocolate. So I've got one of these, why don't you? Why don't

00:37:57.640 --> 00:38:04.240
[Guest]: you go to BBMP and ask them to give you one of these as well? And really from that, the

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:10.800
[Guest]: notion of community-managed public spaces and water bodies in particular began to take

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:16.440
[Guest]: hold. Today, I think there are several dozen lakes in the city which are managed like this,

00:38:16.440 --> 00:38:21.040
[Guest]: all under roughly a similar framework. And then United Way got involved in that and pushed

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:27.360
[Guest]: for a dozen or so lakes to be managed in this way. Some local representatives, MLAs in a

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:32.280
[Guest]: few constituencies were more open to this than others. So it began to grow faster in

00:38:32.280 --> 00:38:40.960
[Guest]: those areas. And really this model of publicly managed problems, I think of the whole thing

00:38:40.960 --> 00:38:46.760
[Guest]: as a public management of the city by the citizens too, and not just the elected representatives

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:54.400
[Guest]: or the officials. And that, in my mind, crystallized in an idea over time, that you don't try to

00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:59.960
[Guest]: solve the problem. You try to increase the number of problems solving people. That's

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:04.560
[Guest]: really what I try to do. I, by and large, don't try to solve problems. I don't know

00:39:04.560 --> 00:39:08.960
[Guest]: the answer to most things. I'm an astronomer. I used to study clouds in Antarctica. What

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:12.320
[Guest]: the hell do I know about all of these things? It's better to ask the guys who've been studying

00:39:12.320 --> 00:39:17.200
[Guest]: these things, how do you solve this problem? And then concentrate on increasing the number

00:39:17.200 --> 00:39:22.360
[Guest]: of people who can go do that. Then there's a chance that some of these... If you look

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:26.760
[Guest]: at the city today, what are some things that have worked well? There are lots of things

00:39:26.760 --> 00:39:30.920
[Guest]: that people say don't work well in Bangalore. And there's some truth to that. But what are

00:39:30.920 --> 00:39:35.520
[Guest]: the things that did work well over the last 10 or 15 years? Some of the police work got

00:39:35.520 --> 00:39:40.440
[Guest]: digitized. Some amount of rationalization of bus services happened. Some amount of public

00:39:40.440 --> 00:39:46.680
[Guest]: space improvement began. Waste management, voluntarily segregative waste management by

00:39:46.680 --> 00:39:51.280
[Guest]: communities began to happen. Here and there, the notion of sustainability took hold in

00:39:51.280 --> 00:40:00.760
[Guest]: a few communities. A large part of what happened positively in the last 10 years or so, I would

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:07.120
[Guest]: put that under the bucket of saying, these are things that happened where the role of

00:40:07.120 --> 00:40:14.280
[Guest]: society was also significant. Society could be a large number of individuals in volunteer

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:19.080
[Guest]: mode, but it could also be people outside the government in knowledge mode, right? Not

00:40:19.080 --> 00:40:23.440
[Guest]: contractors, not vendors, people just bringing knowledge to public problem solving and working

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:31.040
[Guest]: with the government to solve them. And I think that model has legs and merit. When you increase

00:40:31.040 --> 00:40:35.080
[Guest]: the number of problem solving people, you also increase the type of problem solving

00:40:35.080 --> 00:40:39.800
[Guest]: people that come into the thing. And therefore, your approach to problem solving is strengthened

00:40:39.800 --> 00:40:44.720
[Guest]: by that, and you effectively give yourself a higher chance that the problem can be solved.

00:40:44.720 --> 00:40:49.560
[Guest]: So this is a model that we try to run again and again. And so, like for example, when

00:40:49.560 --> 00:40:54.960
[Guest]: we set up BCLIP, this Bangalore Civic Leadership Intubation Program, which is run here at Takshashilam,

00:40:54.960 --> 00:40:59.600
[Guest]: this is again the same idea. You want good corporators, right? Train them before they

00:40:59.600 --> 00:41:03.760
[Guest]: contest the election. So every year you train 100 people to contest corporation elections.

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:08.320
[Guest]: And if you do that over five years, you'll have trained 500 people. There are only 200

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:12.800
[Guest]: seats. You'll train two and a half times the number of people to contest the election.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:17.440
[Guest]: Even if 100 of them or 50 of them contest the election, you suddenly have a cadre of

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:21.960
[Guest]: people who are contesting public representation spaces who have actually been trained in how

00:41:21.960 --> 00:41:27.280
[Guest]: the city works, what it does, and so on and so forth. And then you can get them as part

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:30.920
[Guest]: of that course training itself to say, now go do something in your neighborhood. You're

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:34.440
[Guest]: basically seeding and flooding the system with problem-solving people.

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:39.480
[Amit Varma]: I think that's a lovely and very inspiring frame to look at governance and talking of

00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:43.880
[Amit Varma]: problem-solving people. And this is a subject I keep banging about as well, that population

00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:47.320
[Amit Varma]: is not a problem. People are the ultimate resource and, you know, which you've given

00:41:47.320 --> 00:41:51.840
[Amit Varma]: an illustration of. A thought that kind of strikes me is I've always said that in India,

00:41:51.840 --> 00:41:56.320
[Amit Varma]: the state has basically failed in everything it is supposed to do, it should do, and therefore

00:41:56.320 --> 00:42:02.160
[Amit Varma]: society runs by itself. But mostly society runs by itself in jugaru ways. For example,

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:05.880
[Amit Varma]: if you're not provided with power, you get a generator and you're doing jugar. And the

00:42:05.880 --> 00:42:11.240
[Amit Varma]: model that you've pointed out is one where society runs by itself, but almost in partnership

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:15.240
[Amit Varma]: with the state where you go to the state, and like you say, okay, we will manage our

00:42:15.240 --> 00:42:21.760
[Amit Varma]: own lake and let's do an MOU and you formalize that arrangement and reduce the scope of the

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:26.760
[Amit Varma]: state and build an element of local governance into this where the people who are affected

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:32.320
[Amit Varma]: by the lake are the people who are looking after it. But my question then is that just

00:42:32.320 --> 00:42:35.920
[Amit Varma]: looking at the incentives within government, it would strike me that they would be wary

00:42:35.920 --> 00:42:41.120
[Amit Varma]: of such arrangements because it involves giving up power, it involves giving up budgets, because

00:42:41.120 --> 00:42:45.480
[Amit Varma]: I guess at some level, the engineer of lakes will one day be told you have all these MOUs,

00:42:45.480 --> 00:42:49.920
[Amit Varma]: we can reduce your budgets, you're not doing anything. So how have you dealt with that

00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:55.520
[Amit Varma]: sort of pushback, like your sort of civic slash governance activism that you've done?

00:42:55.520 --> 00:42:59.720
[Amit Varma]: How did you have to, you know, present your proposals? And what were these interactions

00:42:59.720 --> 00:43:01.520
[Guest]: like? How do you win them over to your side?

00:43:01.520 --> 00:43:08.800
[Guest]: Well, it is partly political. I don't think you can deny that. I don't. I think it's important

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:16.240
[Guest]: to be political. Because if you were merely civic about it, the risk that you are pointing

00:43:16.240 --> 00:43:21.280
[Guest]: to can become quite real and quite large as well. But if you are political about it, this

00:43:21.280 --> 00:43:28.160
[Guest]: risk is much more manageable. But you have to say, this is the way I want it, that you're

00:43:28.160 --> 00:43:34.680
[Guest]: going to push for it, you're not merely going to advocate for it. And it also requires a

00:43:34.680 --> 00:43:39.640
[Guest]: different view of development. A lot of people think of development as something that is

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:46.440
[Guest]: delivered either by good administration, or by some new law, or maybe jobs, whatever kind

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:55.400
[Guest]: of thing. But in my mind, I think of development. Development is a state. It's a state of whatever,

00:43:55.400 --> 00:43:56.400
[Guest]: a state of things.

00:43:56.400 --> 00:43:57.400
[Amit Varma]: State of development.

00:43:57.400 --> 00:44:02.160
[Guest]: It's a state, yeah. It's not a state like in a legal state, but in a state of things.

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:08.400
[Guest]: And that state is a balance between the sarkar, the market, and society. That's development.

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:14.440
[Guest]: It's not what it delivers or what it does. Having that balance is itself development.

00:44:14.440 --> 00:44:21.200
[Guest]: That if you don't have that balance, and this is why Nehru's model didn't work, it destroyed

00:44:21.200 --> 00:44:27.280
[Guest]: the balance at birth. And therefore, it had no chance of leading to development. Even

00:44:27.280 --> 00:44:32.720
[Guest]: today, governments, both in the center and the states, are quite strongly wedded to the

00:44:32.720 --> 00:44:39.000
[Guest]: state-led idea. Out of necessity, they may give up a few things. We're not able to run

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:42.600
[Guest]: this company. We're not able to run those banks. We're not able to deliver this outcome

00:44:42.600 --> 00:44:46.920
[Guest]: or that outcome. We'll privatize it. We'll regulate it. We'll do something or the other.

00:44:46.920 --> 00:44:53.040
[Guest]: But fundamentally, I think we are going to lag behind a very large part of the world

00:44:53.040 --> 00:45:00.280
[Guest]: unless we can get to a state of accepting that a peer-to-peer relationship between these

00:45:00.280 --> 00:45:07.040
[Guest]: three actors, state, market, and society, is not just a foundation of development. It's

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:13.520
[Guest]: sort of a guarantor, and it's actually itself a kind of development. And therefore, to pursue

00:45:13.520 --> 00:45:21.200
[Guest]: that means that as an individual, you're acting in all three arenas. You're acting in your

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:28.040
[Guest]: civic social arena. You're acting in the political governance administrative arena. And you are

00:45:28.040 --> 00:45:37.400
[Guest]: acting in the market, industry, commerce arena. That when citizens simultaneously participate

00:45:37.400 --> 00:45:44.680
[Guest]: in all these three, it's very difficult to sort of stop development, actually, in that

00:45:44.680 --> 00:45:45.680
[Guest]: case.

00:45:45.680 --> 00:45:51.000
[Guest]: And I'll give you an example. A lot of people will say, oh, these guys in the municipality

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:56.160
[Guest]: are really awful, and the water board. Yesterday, somebody came and laid the road in front of

00:45:56.160 --> 00:46:00.400
[Guest]: my house. And tomorrow, I mean, the day before, somebody came and laid the road in front of

00:46:00.400 --> 00:46:05.360
[Guest]: my house. And today, somebody's come to dig it up again. Why can't they coordinate their

00:46:05.360 --> 00:46:06.360
[Guest]: work?

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:11.240
[Guest]: And one good question to ask is, you have presented both of these events. What were

00:46:11.240 --> 00:46:16.120
[Guest]: you doing? And a lot of people sort of respond to that by saying, what can I do? I'm just

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:21.640
[Guest]: a regular citizen. And in my experience, there are two things that you can do that will stop

00:46:21.640 --> 00:46:28.560
[Guest]: this quickly. If you know the engineers in your ward, the ones responsible for water

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:34.640
[Guest]: delivery, sewer treatment, as well as for electricity, roads, and all of that stuff,

00:46:34.640 --> 00:46:40.400
[Guest]: it's unlikely that this kind of uncoordinated action would happen. You actually know them.

00:46:40.400 --> 00:46:45.840
[Guest]: So in this meet strategy, one of the useful people to go out and meet is your local officials,

00:46:45.840 --> 00:46:47.520
[Guest]: for example.

00:46:47.520 --> 00:46:53.480
[Guest]: So one is if you know people, you become a kind of coordinator merely by knowing what

00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:59.920
[Guest]: they separately and in silos know. So you can avoid some of this. The second thing is

00:46:59.920 --> 00:47:07.400
[Guest]: that if you sort of are involved in this way, a demonstration effect emerges from that.

00:47:07.400 --> 00:47:12.680
[Guest]: I mean, I live in a neighborhood, which is small, I admit. But in that neighborhood,

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:16.400
[Guest]: there is waste segregation at every doorstep. There's a park, which is maintained by the

00:47:16.400 --> 00:47:20.440
[Guest]: local community. There's a playground that is also maintained locally. There's a lakes

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:25.200
[Guest]: public space, which is maintained by the local community. By and large, it's okay. All the

00:47:25.200 --> 00:47:31.480
[Guest]: things that one goes out and fights for at the local neighborhood level are achievable

00:47:31.480 --> 00:47:36.400
[Guest]: at the local. In fact, we even went one step further. The sewage treatment plant. We built

00:47:36.400 --> 00:47:40.600
[Guest]: a sewage treatment plant in the community even before it was required by law. I'm pretty

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:41.600
[Guest]: sure of that.

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:46.760
[Guest]: And then we said, the lake sometimes goes dry. What if we allowed treated water from

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:51.240
[Guest]: the sewage treatment plant to refill the lake? And by working with the pollution control

00:47:51.240 --> 00:47:56.840
[Guest]: board, we were able to set a treatment standard at which lake refills would be allowed by

00:47:56.840 --> 00:48:01.760
[Guest]: treated sewage water. And that was the first as well. So you suddenly get 4 million liters

00:48:01.760 --> 00:48:07.680
[Guest]: of water going into a lake every day. And what it tells me, and then what it ensures

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:13.080
[Guest]: is the lake is always full. It's a nice public space that's open to a lot of people because

00:48:13.080 --> 00:48:17.120
[Guest]: it's invitingly full with water.

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:21.160
[Guest]: And if you say, okay, what do I care? I care about things like electricity and roads and

00:48:21.160 --> 00:48:25.600
[Guest]: sewage and water and all of those kinds of things and playgrounds and public spaces.

00:48:25.600 --> 00:48:31.840
[Guest]: You could argue that in your sphere of influence, you can create these things by working among

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:37.760
[Guest]: yourselves in a certain way, except that you have to think of this yourselves part as including

00:48:37.760 --> 00:48:43.480
[Guest]: the corporator, including the public officials and a few others as well. Deliberate engagement

00:48:43.480 --> 00:48:49.600
[Guest]: of state market society can produce this outcome. You can even get company CSR to underwrite

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:52.640
[Guest]: a bunch of these things. In a typical community, there are enough people who can find some

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:55.160
[Guest]: sources of company CSR as well.

00:48:55.160 --> 00:49:03.520
[Guest]: So I think we have a model in place that says joint action by citizens, the Sarkar and people

00:49:03.520 --> 00:49:09.640
[Guest]: in businesses can produce outcomes at the local level. The real question in my mind

00:49:09.640 --> 00:49:15.800
[Guest]: is can this also produce large outcomes? And in Bangalore, there's a really good example

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:22.760
[Guest]: of this. The suburban rail project, which is now being implemented is a fantastic example

00:49:22.760 --> 00:49:29.400
[Guest]: of it. The suburban rail project came out of just a few people themselves studying the

00:49:29.400 --> 00:49:34.760
[Guest]: tracks around the city, utilization on those tracks, figuring out what the spare capacity

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:40.000
[Guest]: might be and figuring out which neighborhoods and which tech parks and other destinations

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:45.200
[Guest]: could be usefully connected about it and putting that together as a proposal to start running

00:49:45.200 --> 00:49:51.320
[Guest]: commuter trains in the peripheral areas. And it started just a handful of people. And the

00:49:51.320 --> 00:49:57.160
[Guest]: fact that they were able to advocate it to a point of making it a popular demand, getting

00:49:57.160 --> 00:50:03.440
[Guest]: an SPV established for this purpose, funded, and now trains are beginning to roll on that

00:50:03.440 --> 00:50:10.480
[Guest]: track tells you that it's not just small problems that get solved by this kind of way of thinking

00:50:10.480 --> 00:50:15.560
[Guest]: about development, but it has potential to solve some really large problems too.

00:50:15.560 --> 00:50:20.160
[Amit Varma]: And so this is, again, a very interesting model. And I guess for something like the

00:50:20.160 --> 00:50:25.440
[Amit Varma]: suburban railway system, you need, first of all, policy geek type of people who are actually

00:50:25.440 --> 00:50:30.240
[Amit Varma]: sitting down and making those calculations and then more activist type of people who

00:50:30.240 --> 00:50:36.360
[Amit Varma]: can spread those ideas in public and negotiators who can then talk to government about those

00:50:36.360 --> 00:50:41.560
[Amit Varma]: things. The point that sort of interested me about what you said previously is that

00:50:41.560 --> 00:50:46.400
[Amit Varma]: my question about the incentives of bureaucrats and government is misplaced because you also

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:52.280
[Amit Varma]: did it in a political way. And the incentives of politicians are obviously to respond to

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:57.640
[Amit Varma]: the demands of the marketplace, where at the supply end, therefore, your challenge is to

00:50:57.640 --> 00:51:04.240
[Amit Varma]: create enough of a demand within local communities. And then governments sort of have no option.

00:51:04.240 --> 00:51:05.240
[Amit Varma]: I'll ask you to...

00:51:05.240 --> 00:51:11.520
[Guest]: I'll give you a useful tip in this. Whatever you say to your executive engineer, world

00:51:11.520 --> 00:51:16.520
[Guest]: level engineer, executive engineer, tell it to his supervisor also. And whatever you tell

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:19.760
[Guest]: to him, tell it to your zonal commissioner also. Whatever you tell to him, tell it to

00:51:19.760 --> 00:51:23.720
[Guest]: a corporator also. Whatever you tell your corporator, tell your MLA also. Whatever you

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:29.080
[Guest]: tell your MLA, tell the minister in charge also. And let each guy know that you will

00:51:29.080 --> 00:51:36.720
[Guest]: be telling it to the guy above him. And this is, I do this very consciously and intentionally.

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:39.160
[Amit Varma]: I think it's important.

00:51:39.160 --> 00:51:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And they're all listening to this episode now and going, whoa, Ashwin.

00:51:42.440 --> 00:51:47.040
[Guest]: No, they know it also. But now they sort of know that I know the guy above them also.

00:51:47.040 --> 00:51:50.840
[Guest]: In the beginning, I didn't know the guy above them. So you sort of have to make an effort.

00:51:50.840 --> 00:51:56.040
[Guest]: Now, I actually know the guy above them as well. But I think, I'll tell you what it is.

00:51:56.040 --> 00:52:02.200
[Guest]: Because you'd never really know who is potentially supportive, who is an obstacle, number one.

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:06.000
[Guest]: So you want to bring clarity to that by saying the same thing to many people and say, okay,

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:10.640
[Guest]: let's all have this conversation. The second thing is that sometimes people will come back

00:52:10.640 --> 00:52:13.880
[Guest]: and say, sir, we can't do it because my boss is not agreeing or the minister is not agreeing

00:52:13.880 --> 00:52:18.720
[Guest]: or MLA is not agreeing. So you want to be able to bypass that, kind of block it and

00:52:18.720 --> 00:52:23.760
[Guest]: say, I want to be able to do it. That's all it is, right? And I feel it's important. And

00:52:23.760 --> 00:52:31.920
[Guest]: again, increasing the number of problem-solving people disciplines the opposition to it also.

00:52:31.920 --> 00:52:36.960
[Guest]: You can't be frivolous in opposition. You have to give reasons.

00:52:36.960 --> 00:52:39.760
[Amit Varma]: Because you know that everyone in the chain is also listening in.

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:45.280
[Guest]: Yeah. And also, I used to run, when I was in government, I used to run a coordination

00:52:45.280 --> 00:52:50.600
[Guest]: committee for South Bangalore. And you and I are living in our houses thinking that the

00:52:50.600 --> 00:52:54.280
[Guest]: municipality and the water board and the electricity board, all these guys are going to work together

00:52:54.280 --> 00:52:58.240
[Guest]: for our benefit. But if you go to a coordination meeting, you'll realize something else. Each

00:52:58.240 --> 00:53:02.040
[Guest]: one of them is complaining about the other and saying, you know, this guy's not letting

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:05.400
[Guest]: me do my job. That guy's not returning the road to me. These guys aren't willing to close

00:53:05.400 --> 00:53:09.360
[Guest]: the road, you know, traffic police, all sorts of things. And so you spend all your time

00:53:09.360 --> 00:53:15.280
[Guest]: not solving public's problems, but actually resolving their own internal silos.

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:19.560
[Guest]: But after you do that for three weeks, four weeks, they know each other. In fact, the

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:24.280
[Guest]: first meeting that I had of this coordination committee, the different engineers looked

00:53:24.280 --> 00:53:28.320
[Guest]: at each other and effectively said, who are these people? They never even met them. And

00:53:28.320 --> 00:53:35.160
[Guest]: yet you and I are counting on them to collaborate and coordinate for outcomes. And I think that's

00:53:35.160 --> 00:53:40.120
[Guest]: why it's important that sometimes the silos only get broken by being deliberate about

00:53:40.120 --> 00:53:41.120
[Guest]: bringing people together.

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:45.320
[Amit Varma]: We'll take a quick commercial break now. And when we come back, get down to the nuts and

00:53:45.320 --> 00:53:52.040
[Amit Varma]: bolts of participatory democracy or government by the people, as you put it.

