[Amit Varma]: the code unseen, U-N-S-E-E-N. That's unseen for 15% off at IndianColors.com.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:06.600
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen. I'm chatting with Ashwin Mahesh, who I consider

00:55:06.600 --> 00:55:11.880
[Amit Varma]: a sort of a guru of urban governance and so on, but who has also dabbled in politics.

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:17.680
[Amit Varma]: He was part of the Lok Satta Party, started by J.P. Narayan, another intellectual hero

00:55:17.680 --> 00:55:22.520
[Amit Varma]: of mine with whom I've had a couple of episodes in the past. And then he was there at the

00:55:22.520 --> 00:55:27.240
[Amit Varma]: birth of India Against Corruption. He played a big role in that and is now part of the

00:55:27.240 --> 00:55:31.880
[Amit Varma]: Aam Aadmi Party, in fact. So again, to go back to biography, at what point did you think

00:55:31.880 --> 00:55:35.800
[Amit Varma]: that you also have to get politically involved for things to happen?

00:55:35.800 --> 00:55:42.560
[Guest]: Well, you know, in my mind, I've never accepted this separation between political and not

00:55:42.560 --> 00:55:50.000
[Guest]: political. I'm trying to solve public problems. And whatever arena of action you need to be

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:56.600
[Guest]: in for that, that's what you need to do. In the late 90s, when Subbu Vincent and I started

00:55:56.600 --> 00:56:00.640
[Guest]: India Together, we started publishing this development magazine, which I still edit and

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:06.440
[Guest]: publish. And one of the things that happened to me during the first six or eight years

00:56:06.440 --> 00:56:11.440
[Guest]: of publishing India Together is that lots and lots of people in civil society and development

00:56:11.440 --> 00:56:17.160
[Guest]: organizations, maybe even sometimes in government, wrote articles for the publication. And it

00:56:17.160 --> 00:56:22.920
[Guest]: was a digital thing, but Subbu and I edited most of it ourselves. And the very act of

00:56:22.920 --> 00:56:29.600
[Guest]: editing all these articles brought me to some understanding of what's going on in the power

00:56:29.600 --> 00:56:32.560
[Guest]: sector, what's going on in the environment, what's going on in water supply, what's going

00:56:32.560 --> 00:56:38.240
[Guest]: on in cities. It's basically, it's a daily education. Generalists are educating you daily.

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:42.200
[Guest]: You just have to apply your mind and make sure the content is streamlined well and presented

00:56:42.200 --> 00:56:48.680
[Guest]: well and all of that. And at some point, you begin to realize that a big part of the obstacle

00:56:48.680 --> 00:56:54.000
[Guest]: to development is political, that it's not merely an administrative matter. It's not

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:59.640
[Guest]: about getting the governance right and the staffing right and the budgets right and all

00:56:59.640 --> 00:57:02.640
[Guest]: that. There's an element of willpower. There's an element of vested interest. There's an

00:57:02.640 --> 00:57:08.080
[Guest]: element of collusion and corruption, all of that stuff that needs to be overcome as well.

00:57:08.080 --> 00:57:13.720
[Guest]: You just know that. And you also recognize that a lot of this is coming from problems

00:57:13.720 --> 00:57:19.840
[Guest]: in the electoral system. So in the, I'm going to say second half of the 90s, there was this

00:57:19.840 --> 00:57:25.160
[Guest]: thing called the NCER, the National Campaign for Electoral Reforms. And that's when I first

00:57:25.160 --> 00:57:32.040
[Guest]: began to work with JP. He, of course, sort of, in my mind, sort of pushed the idea of

00:57:32.040 --> 00:57:37.120
[Guest]: administrative reforms and electoral reforms onto the national attention landscape more

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:41.320
[Guest]: than anybody else. And so it was a good place for me to sort of figure out this thing. And

00:57:41.320 --> 00:57:45.600
[Guest]: I just started doing India Together as a digital platform. And so I said many of the things

00:57:45.600 --> 00:57:50.400
[Guest]: that we are trying only in non-digital ways, we should try in digital ways as well. And

00:57:50.400 --> 00:57:55.520
[Guest]: I think even he sort of saw the power of that and it actually became something. Some things

00:57:55.520 --> 00:58:01.800
[Guest]: even happened in parliament through his interventions in electoral reforms or the capping the size

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:05.400
[Guest]: of the cabinet, for example, disclosure of assets and backgrounds. All of these things

00:58:05.400 --> 00:58:13.320
[Guest]: happened through the NCER campaign and others who were doing similar work. And over time,

00:58:13.320 --> 00:58:17.560
[Guest]: when you come to know everybody, you know what Aruna and Nikhil are doing in MKSS and

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:23.040
[Guest]: the right to information. You know what Arvind is doing with Parivartan in the public distribution

00:58:23.040 --> 00:58:27.160
[Guest]: system. Over time, around the country, you begin to know who's doing what in different

00:58:27.160 --> 00:58:33.080
[Guest]: fields, what's working, what's not working. And you also know all of these people as individuals

00:58:33.080 --> 00:58:40.320
[Guest]: in some ways. And you can here and there find things that you can do with them. And so when

00:58:40.320 --> 00:58:44.560
[Guest]: I came back to India as well, for two years, I worked closely with JP in the Administrative

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:50.360
[Guest]: Reforms Commission. The first four reports on right to information, the National Employment

00:58:50.360 --> 00:58:56.480
[Guest]: Guarantee, public order, and one more of those reports. I worked on those with him. And then

00:58:56.480 --> 00:59:01.320
[Guest]: that gives you an understanding of how the law and order system works, how our file movement

00:59:01.320 --> 00:59:04.840
[Guest]: and disclosure of information can be improved in government. It's things like livelihood

00:59:04.840 --> 00:59:11.120
[Guest]: in rural area. And for me, all of this was partly an education, but also partly an invitation

00:59:11.120 --> 00:59:14.880
[Guest]: to do something, right? Because you're sort of standing in the space and you can see the

00:59:14.880 --> 00:59:23.280
[Guest]: problem in front of you. And you don't have to be moved very much to begin doing something

00:59:23.280 --> 00:59:31.600
[Guest]: about it. And then partway through the Administrative Reforms Commission, JP had more or less made

00:59:31.600 --> 00:59:38.360
[Guest]: up his mind to form Lok Satta as a political party. I think Lok Satta is an interesting

00:59:38.360 --> 00:59:45.080
[Guest]: idea because I think for the first time, somebody in India was saying there should be a liberal

00:59:45.080 --> 00:59:50.920
[Guest]: political party. I mean, there are other claimants to this idea. I'm not going to dispute that.

00:59:50.920 --> 00:59:56.880
[Guest]: But I think on the ground to try it out as an experiment with some potential for scale

00:59:56.880 --> 01:00:02.640
[Guest]: coming from a popular figure known across the state at least. Lok Satta was a good experiment.

01:00:02.640 --> 01:00:07.880
[Guest]: It was a really good experiment. And I remember participating in the early writings of the

01:00:07.880 --> 01:00:13.520
[Guest]: constitution, the manifestos, and things like that. And subsequently, I sort of wrote down

01:00:13.520 --> 01:00:20.120
[Guest]: some 11 or 12 points, which I think going forward can be part of a liberal manifesto

01:00:20.120 --> 01:00:27.480
[Guest]: again and again. And I also began to see the ways in which a liberal view alone would be

01:00:27.480 --> 01:00:34.200
[Guest]: inadequate in the Indian context. And a federal view also needed to intersect the liberal

01:00:34.200 --> 01:00:39.040
[Guest]: view. And more recently, about two years ago, I wrote the federal manifesto points down

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:44.360
[Guest]: as well for me to sort of see where all these intersections happen. And by and large, I

01:00:44.360 --> 01:00:50.560
[Guest]: did that as an exercise for myself to say, what do I believe about these public problems,

01:00:50.560 --> 01:00:54.760
[Guest]: about the nature of the state, about the nature of citizenship and society and markets and

01:00:54.760 --> 01:01:03.120
[Guest]: all of that? And what do I believe will be effective as a method to development? And

01:01:03.120 --> 01:01:09.080
[Guest]: I think even though I wrote these things down primarily for myself, I was able to over time

01:01:09.080 --> 01:01:14.400
[Guest]: develop those into things that I could communicate to other people and share. And some interesting

01:01:14.400 --> 01:01:20.200
[Guest]: people have contributed. Barun, for example, has been part of that. I've learned from other

01:01:20.200 --> 01:01:27.520
[Guest]: people who have thought about similar problems as well. But I think the future really does

01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:33.840
[Guest]: depend critically on how we attain this balance, the balance in center-state relationships,

01:01:33.840 --> 01:01:38.640
[Guest]: the balance between the private and the public, the balance between the state market and society.

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:45.480
[Guest]: Ultimately, I think of balance as the foundation for development. And so I was fascinated when

01:01:45.480 --> 01:01:50.520
[Guest]: Lok Sattar came up as a political party. I was in it from the very beginning. I eventually

01:01:50.520 --> 01:01:57.640
[Guest]: became vice president of Lok Sattar as well. And it was kind of interesting. We tried various

01:01:57.640 --> 01:02:04.640
[Guest]: things. I think electorally, apart from JP's victory in the MLA elections, I forget which

01:02:04.640 --> 01:02:12.280
[Guest]: year, 2008, in one year in Andhra Pradesh. Electorally, there wasn't a whole lot that

01:02:12.280 --> 01:02:19.840
[Guest]: Lok Sattar was able to show. But I think it remained an important inspirational idea for

01:02:19.840 --> 01:02:24.600
[Guest]: a lot of people who sensed that our current approach to politics and public problem solving

01:02:24.600 --> 01:02:29.960
[Guest]: itself is wrong. That no matter how much you invest in the current approach, you could

01:02:29.960 --> 01:02:35.800
[Guest]: not get to an idea of development. That Lok Sattar's view of a more liberal, more federated,

01:02:35.800 --> 01:02:43.840
[Guest]: more participatory, more decentralized approach to development simply had more potential,

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:50.840
[Guest]: whether you agreed with it or not, whether you agreed with all of it or not. And I think

01:02:50.840 --> 01:02:56.400
[Guest]: Lok Sattar remains an inspiration for people who sort of saw that. But obviously, you sort

01:02:56.400 --> 01:03:03.120
[Guest]: of, at the end of India Against Corruption, I'm going to skip through to go to the political

01:03:03.120 --> 01:03:08.560
[Guest]: part and then we'll come back to IAC. At the end of India Against Corruption, or towards

01:03:08.560 --> 01:03:14.080
[Guest]: the end of IAC, the graduate constituency elections came up in Bangalore. And I said,

01:03:14.080 --> 01:03:19.400
[Guest]: it's not a bad thing. It's a limited electorate. It's a citywide electorate of only educated

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:25.160
[Guest]: people. Maybe there's something we can try in this thing. And so the first time that

01:03:25.160 --> 01:03:29.840
[Guest]: I contested an election, I was doing it, and even the second time, I was doing it only

01:03:29.840 --> 01:03:38.320
[Guest]: for one reason, to say that it is possible, both possible and necessary, for public-spirited

01:03:38.320 --> 01:03:46.960
[Guest]: but normal citizens to contest public office. That if we left this to merely lifelong political

01:03:46.960 --> 01:03:51.880
[Guest]: players with really nothing else to do in life besides politics, you're not going to

01:03:51.880 --> 01:03:57.720
[Guest]: get any idea of development from that. And the graduate constituency election was phenomenal.

01:03:57.720 --> 01:04:07.440
[Guest]: I think some of the people who participated in it, Raj Shekhar Maram, Mastan, Srinivas

01:04:07.440 --> 01:04:14.160
[Guest]: Alwale, people who sort of really gave their day, their life, whatever it is, to make that

01:04:14.160 --> 01:04:19.920
[Guest]: campaign move. And the number of communities that sense that something different could

01:04:19.920 --> 01:04:27.080
[Guest]: be done differently if we get into all this. It was very inspiring and interesting for

01:04:27.080 --> 01:04:33.080
[Guest]: me. We came, I would say, reasonably close. But I think with more time, the problem in

01:04:33.080 --> 01:04:38.600
[Guest]: the graduate constituency election is registering new voters, which is rigged in a certain way

01:04:38.600 --> 01:04:42.360
[Guest]: that makes it difficult to break through. But with some superhuman efforts, we came

01:04:42.360 --> 01:04:47.960
[Guest]: fairly close to doing that. And we also realized that there were some interesting things possible

01:04:47.960 --> 01:04:54.960
[Guest]: in the process. There was one constituency in which the local MLA, who I knew well by

01:04:54.960 --> 01:04:59.840
[Guest]: then, he said, you know, in my mind, I'm convinced that you're the best candidate. But I can't

01:04:59.840 --> 01:05:06.760
[Guest]: go against my party. Right? So here's what I'll do. I'll not campaign against you. And

01:05:06.760 --> 01:05:13.240
[Guest]: when people say things like that, you realize the politics is what it is. Partisanship is

01:05:13.240 --> 01:05:19.000
[Guest]: what it is. But underneath that partisanship, there is potential for people to collaborate

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:24.560
[Guest]: for the public good. But fundamentally, a subset of the political class, I won't say

01:05:24.560 --> 01:05:32.040
[Guest]: all, a subset of the political class is willing to acknowledge that we need to be purposeful.

01:05:32.040 --> 01:05:36.840
[Guest]: And that if people come forward who seem to be purposeful, genuinely, they will cross

01:05:36.840 --> 01:05:44.280
[Guest]: party lines. And on voting day, in the graduate constituency election, there's about some

01:05:44.280 --> 01:05:50.560
[Guest]: 15, 20 voting booths set up all over the city. And I went around a lot of them. In many of

01:05:50.560 --> 01:05:56.960
[Guest]: the booths, the local Congress co-operator or the BJP co-operator or MLA would come out,

01:05:56.960 --> 01:06:01.480
[Guest]: spend time, take pictures with me. And just to say, you know, it's interesting that we're

01:06:01.480 --> 01:06:06.680
[Guest]: doing this differently. This kind of change is necessary. You may not be from our party,

01:06:06.680 --> 01:06:12.200
[Guest]: but this is an important thing. And I felt that there is potential to work across party

01:06:12.200 --> 01:06:17.800
[Guest]: lines in a lot of this. Adwaniji said this, that during his time in politics, there was

01:06:17.800 --> 01:06:25.080
[Guest]: a lot more cross party engagement. And one of the things we sort of lamented almost eight

01:06:25.080 --> 01:06:30.880
[Guest]: or nine years ago is the erosion of cross party collaboration in a lot of this.

01:06:30.880 --> 01:06:37.000
[Guest]: So my first forays in politics were primarily to say, anyone can do this. It's not winning

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:42.560
[Guest]: and losing, actually, that matters. But once you establish the idea that anyone can do

01:06:42.560 --> 01:06:47.760
[Guest]: this, then more and more people begin to come into it, that ordinary people can, in fact,

01:06:47.760 --> 01:06:52.480
[Guest]: collectively express an interest in a certain kind of government and form a political party

01:06:52.480 --> 01:06:59.160
[Guest]: for that reason, contest an election and go forward with it. And if you look it up, really,

01:06:59.160 --> 01:07:02.880
[Guest]: it means that narrative, certainly. You've come together, you form a political party

01:07:02.880 --> 01:07:08.200
[Guest]: for a reason and a certain idea of government, and you go out, contest and even win. And

01:07:08.200 --> 01:07:17.760
[Guest]: I look at what happened in Delhi as really a better kind of proof of the idea that had

01:07:17.760 --> 01:07:24.240
[Guest]: even previously existed, that we could challenge the conventional space. Lok Satta had not

01:07:24.240 --> 01:07:31.600
[Guest]: been adequately strong and adequately, one could even say adequately purposeful in tackling

01:07:31.600 --> 01:07:38.640
[Guest]: that challenge. But maybe perhaps benefiting from the moment offered by India against corruption

01:07:38.640 --> 01:07:43.800
[Guest]: was able to do that. And I think having opened the door a little bit, now there is potential

01:07:43.800 --> 01:07:52.280
[Guest]: to open the door much wider. It remains to be seen. So now I'll go back to IAC, because

01:07:52.280 --> 01:07:59.240
[Guest]: I sort of went from my interest before IAC to after. IAC is kind of an interesting beast,

01:07:59.240 --> 01:08:06.680
[Guest]: because broadly, there were multiple starting points to it. And I have some, it's like touching

01:08:06.680 --> 01:08:11.040
[Guest]: an elephant at some level. Even the people who are standing next to it can't see all

01:08:11.040 --> 01:08:17.920
[Guest]: of it. And it went in certain ways, and it didn't go in certain ways. The first anti-corruption

01:08:17.920 --> 01:08:25.080
[Guest]: rally that we did was actually here in Bangalore. Arvind was visiting, I think he was visiting

01:08:25.080 --> 01:08:34.440
[Guest]: CIVIC perhaps, one of the local NGOs. JP was also in at the same time. And it sort of occurred

01:08:34.440 --> 01:08:43.200
[Guest]: to a few people, Rithvireddy, Rajmaram, Amarmurthy, a few people that we could, Srinivasan, that

01:08:43.200 --> 01:08:53.960
[Guest]: we could use this opportunity to put out a public protest against corruption in governments.

01:08:53.960 --> 01:09:01.800
[Guest]: And that was, we called it SAKU, and it was organized. It was a nice winter morning in

01:09:01.800 --> 01:09:06.960
[Guest]: Covent Park. It was a fantastic day to be out on the street. I like to say a fantastic

01:09:06.960 --> 01:09:12.800
[Guest]: day to protest as well. And about 3,000 people came to that. And people who were well-regarded

01:09:12.800 --> 01:09:18.960
[Guest]: figures in society also showed up at that meeting. I won't go into who is who, but it

01:09:18.960 --> 01:09:24.360
[Guest]: made us realize two things. That there was possibly a way to engage with people who normally

01:09:24.360 --> 01:09:31.240
[Guest]: wouldn't step out of their homes to participate in public expressions of anger and demands

01:09:31.240 --> 01:09:37.480
[Guest]: for certain things. That there is a latent demand for change in the political space.

01:09:37.480 --> 01:09:42.840
[Guest]: And I remember, and then there was a sort of a speech, slash whatever, at the Langford

01:09:42.840 --> 01:09:48.760
[Guest]: Town Park. I think it's called Akhita Manali Park. And we were sort of sitting on some

01:09:48.760 --> 01:09:55.560
[Guest]: ambassador car under one tree and just talking about this. And then the sort of the idea,

01:09:55.560 --> 01:09:59.960
[Guest]: the idea, the discussion moved to the idea of saying, what if you did this everywhere?

01:09:59.960 --> 01:10:06.240
[Guest]: And Arvind had at that time been experimenting with something called group vote. And group

01:10:06.240 --> 01:10:12.120
[Guest]: vote was the idea which he wanted to try in the Municipal Council election. That essentially

01:10:12.120 --> 01:10:19.760
[Guest]: you get clusters of people to vote together, either for a candidate or for a certain goal.

01:10:19.760 --> 01:10:24.320
[Guest]: And the power of this collective vote could discipline the electoral process that much

01:10:24.320 --> 01:10:30.120
[Guest]: more. He was already sort of experimenting with that. In parallel, of course, the demand

01:10:30.120 --> 01:10:38.400
[Guest]: for the Lokpal was going on. So there are three pieces, at least. The emergence of spontaneous

01:10:38.400 --> 01:10:45.000
[Guest]: protest by people in different cities who broadly know each other, but whose origins

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:53.200
[Guest]: for protesting are quite disparate. The efforts in those respective geographies for changing

01:10:53.200 --> 01:11:02.960
[Guest]: the political and electoral system. And the Lokpal as a Lokpal Bill as a focal point for

01:11:02.960 --> 01:11:11.560
[Guest]: intervention and various things that happened in that. And somehow it just came together

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:17.120
[Guest]: in some way that it just went from that first rally to the next one and the next one. And

01:11:17.120 --> 01:11:22.600
[Guest]: before you know it, there was very large number of people. And I'm going to say this, which

01:11:22.600 --> 01:11:25.600
[Guest]: I don't really have. There are a couple of things that I haven't really talked about

01:11:25.600 --> 01:11:29.800
[Guest]: publicly. And I know many people in IAC don't talk about this publicly. I'm going to say

01:11:29.800 --> 01:11:39.560
[Guest]: Anna was not there in the beginning. He had, of course, led his own campaigns for change

01:11:39.560 --> 01:11:44.680
[Guest]: in the electoral system, change in the governance system, including articulating a demand for

01:11:44.680 --> 01:11:48.160
[Guest]: the Lokpal. Around the same time that we held this first rally, he had written to the Prime

01:11:48.160 --> 01:11:54.640
[Guest]: Minister, Dr. Singh at that time, essentially saying, I'm going to sit on fast if we don't

01:11:54.640 --> 01:12:00.800
[Guest]: do this. At that point, of course, it wasn't really an IAC action or anything like that.

01:12:00.800 --> 01:12:06.680
[Guest]: It was just saying, I want this damn law and we're going to push for it. And it was kind

01:12:06.680 --> 01:12:14.680
[Guest]: of funny because in March, as Anna's fast date approached, somebody from the government

01:12:14.680 --> 01:12:18.600
[Guest]: called me up and said, you have a copy of this letter that he wrote to the Prime Minister.

01:12:18.600 --> 01:12:23.040
[Guest]: We can't even seem to find it. And one of the things that happened in IAC, it's kind

01:12:23.040 --> 01:12:28.280
[Guest]: of an interesting thing what has happened in IAC and since IAC. Congress and civil society,

01:12:28.280 --> 01:12:34.840
[Guest]: because of this thing that I told you earlier about NGOs emerging as intermediaries in the

01:12:34.840 --> 01:12:41.960
[Guest]: idea of good Indianness, Congress and civil society have historically been allies. IAC

01:12:41.960 --> 01:12:50.520
[Guest]: effectively chopped that off by basically saying this intermediation is no longer required.

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:54.600
[Guest]: That those who want to speak for a different idea of government should be able to just

01:12:54.600 --> 01:13:03.960
[Guest]: get away from that thing and do it themselves in a way. The Lokpal became a point of focus.

01:13:03.960 --> 01:13:12.560
[Guest]: And then a few days before the first planned protest in early April, there was a meeting

01:13:12.560 --> 01:13:20.040
[Guest]: around that time in Delhi. JP had called that meeting, calling people from different organizations

01:13:20.040 --> 01:13:26.420
[Guest]: together. Maybe that was later in July or something. But I remember there was a time

01:13:26.420 --> 01:13:30.720
[Guest]: that year where JP sort of called a lot of different people. And there were three broadly

01:13:30.720 --> 01:13:37.320
[Guest]: during the struggle for the Lokpal bill. There were three broad versions of the bill. Arvind

01:13:37.320 --> 01:13:45.400
[Guest]: with his sort of allies had put together a version. I mean, which was presented as broadly

01:13:45.400 --> 01:13:51.240
[Guest]: through IAC. Lok Sattar had drafted its version, which subsequently even Dr. Singh sort of

01:13:51.240 --> 01:13:56.440
[Guest]: seemed to embrace a little bit in Parliament. Aruna and Nikhil had put forward another set

01:13:56.440 --> 01:14:00.640
[Guest]: of views on how sort of thing. So there was a little bit of an effort to try to see whether

01:14:00.640 --> 01:14:05.640
[Guest]: all of this could come together. That didn't go very well. That didn't go very well. But

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:12.560
[Guest]: I think it did help coalesce a lot of different people around the idea that there are shared

01:14:12.560 --> 01:14:17.120
[Guest]: goals here. That if you're going to go different ways about it, and even if you have strong

01:14:17.120 --> 01:14:21.880
[Guest]: opinions about your methods or my methods, we're going to fundamentally have to accept

01:14:21.880 --> 01:14:29.040
[Guest]: that these things are broadly what they are. And I think broadly, if people didn't speak

01:14:29.040 --> 01:14:34.600
[Guest]: poorly of each other, that was at least the minimum that you could expect in that. And

01:14:34.600 --> 01:14:43.840
[Guest]: I think that's still true. There's a lot of affection and respect across that whole spectrum

01:14:43.840 --> 01:14:49.120
[Guest]: of participants in India against corruption, even if there are differences about what should

01:14:49.120 --> 01:14:57.120
[Guest]: have been done here or there. And you know that story. It went where it went. And then

01:14:57.120 --> 01:15:03.240
[Guest]: came the question of... I'm skipping past a lot of details of what happened during the

01:15:03.240 --> 01:15:09.520
[Guest]: fast in Delhi. I don't think... Those are interesting tidbits, but we'll save those

01:15:09.520 --> 01:15:15.920
[Guest]: for another day. But really the question that came up after the campaign was the question

01:15:15.920 --> 01:15:23.880
[Guest]: of forming a political party. And this forming of the political party included another event

01:15:23.880 --> 01:15:30.800
[Guest]: about which not much is known. And this is the meeting of the Constitution Club to...

01:15:30.800 --> 01:15:35.400
[Guest]: Essentially Anna had convened, I'm going to say about 60 to 70 people, to put the question

01:15:35.400 --> 01:15:40.880
[Guest]: to a discussant group like that to say... And he'd even said, by and large, I don't

01:15:40.880 --> 01:15:45.760
[Guest]: want this to be an IAC event, because if you sort of turn it into an IAC event, the same

01:15:45.760 --> 01:15:50.480
[Guest]: set of you guys who, quote-unquote, ran the event at some level, would probably stack

01:15:50.480 --> 01:15:56.520
[Guest]: the deck against the decisions being frank. I mean, the conversations being frank. So

01:15:56.520 --> 01:16:00.520
[Guest]: we said we're all quite open to take inputs from anybody else. That was the first time

01:16:00.520 --> 01:16:07.920
[Guest]: I met Yogendra Yadav in one of these kinds of settings. He was part moderator of that

01:16:07.920 --> 01:16:11.880
[Guest]: discussion. People from all over the country would come from different walks of life there.

01:16:11.880 --> 01:16:16.560
[Guest]: I think it was also the first time I met Ashutosh. And just a few people who didn't really come

01:16:16.560 --> 01:16:25.240
[Guest]: in through the movement, but who saw the potential that it had and people who sort of engaged

01:16:25.240 --> 01:16:30.360
[Guest]: with it in their own way, and subsequently even became strong parts of it, were starting

01:16:30.360 --> 01:16:37.120
[Guest]: to come together. And without elaborating... And there were not that many people from IAC.

01:16:37.120 --> 01:16:43.200
[Guest]: Arvind was there, I was there, Prashant was there, Kiran was there, of course, at that

01:16:43.200 --> 01:16:50.080
[Guest]: time. There were not that many people from IAC itself. And just to say... Broadly, I

01:16:50.080 --> 01:16:55.920
[Guest]: would say... I'll say only one thing, and I'm not going to elaborate on that. Throughout

01:16:55.920 --> 01:17:01.640
[Guest]: the day's conversation, it was broadly agreed among the discussions that it's useful and

01:17:01.640 --> 01:17:07.160
[Guest]: healthy to form a political party to take this forward. And that if the political party

01:17:07.160 --> 01:17:12.440
[Guest]: appeared to stray towards the normal traditional politics of every party, we must have the

01:17:12.440 --> 01:17:18.640
[Guest]: discipline to either exit that thing, or the forcefulness to correct course and keep going

01:17:18.640 --> 01:17:25.200
[Guest]: forward. And broadly, this is how that discussion went. Various people said it is possible to

01:17:25.200 --> 01:17:29.160
[Guest]: build that kind of political organization, and that it is necessary to build at least

01:17:29.160 --> 01:17:38.480
[Guest]: one example of that in India. My sense of it is, throughout the day, Anna agreed with

01:17:38.480 --> 01:17:43.040
[Guest]: a lot of the stuff. But he went out and said the opposite. And that's all I'm going to

01:17:43.040 --> 01:17:51.520
[Guest]: say about it. I mean, there has been a divergence with Anna. I don't deny that. But I didn't

01:17:51.520 --> 01:17:59.120
[Guest]: think that divergence came from anything that we said or he said to each other. It happened

01:17:59.120 --> 01:18:06.760
[Guest]: in whatever way it happened. But it also became not that important from that point onwards.

01:18:06.760 --> 01:18:13.720
[Guest]: Because anyway, I think as a group, the discussion seemed to indicate a direction to go in. And

01:18:13.720 --> 01:18:19.360
[Guest]: quickly thereafter, the party was formed. And by November, it was actually launched.

01:18:19.360 --> 01:18:25.360
[Guest]: So once you've moved to that point, yes, you would have the occasional thing in the news

01:18:25.360 --> 01:18:30.320
[Guest]: headlines about Annaji having this opinion or that opinion, or being happy about this,

01:18:30.320 --> 01:18:35.560
[Guest]: unhappy about that, and all of that. But broadly, it was done. That day, broadly, the divergence

01:18:35.560 --> 01:18:45.800
[Guest]: began. And IAC as a campaign, I won't say that was the end of it. But it was understood

01:18:45.800 --> 01:18:52.240
[Guest]: from that point onward, that even the Lokpal Agenda had to be taken forward from there

01:18:52.240 --> 01:19:00.160
[Guest]: onwards in the political space only that the sort of civic, public spirited, public purpose

01:19:00.160 --> 01:19:07.480
[Guest]: campaign that IAC had been without other people's participation and support. That mode was over.

01:19:07.480 --> 01:19:11.960
[Guest]: But you now have to sort of take this up as a political question only. And that's where

01:19:11.960 --> 01:19:12.960
[Amit Varma]: it ended.

01:19:12.960 --> 01:19:18.600
[Amit Varma]: So I did a recent episode on radically networked societies with Pranay Kutasane, where we sort

01:19:18.600 --> 01:19:23.640
[Amit Varma]: of looked at movements of the past, like the Arab Spring and even before. And, you know,

01:19:23.640 --> 01:19:27.760
[Amit Varma]: one interesting point that the author Zainab Tufekci made in her book, Twitter and Tear

01:19:27.760 --> 01:19:33.280
[Amit Varma]: Gas about such movements, is that there are three sort of dimensions through which you

01:19:33.280 --> 01:19:38.200
[Amit Varma]: have to look at them. One, you have to look at the narrative capacity, how they build

01:19:38.200 --> 01:19:41.800
[Amit Varma]: a narrative around a particular thing, which IAC, of course, did very successfully with

01:19:41.800 --> 01:19:46.280
[Amit Varma]: the, you know, making corruption the focus of it. Second, you have to look at the disruptive

01:19:46.280 --> 01:19:50.800
[Amit Varma]: capacity, where again, it would seem that it worked out well with IAC. And the third

01:19:50.800 --> 01:19:56.080
[Amit Varma]: is you have to look at the electoral slash political capacity. And a lot of these other

01:19:56.080 --> 01:20:01.160
[Amit Varma]: movements of the Arab Spring really fizzled out without doing much in the political sphere.

01:20:01.160 --> 01:20:06.200
[Amit Varma]: Some like, you know, like Syriza in Greece, for example, came out of a movement and achieve

01:20:06.200 --> 01:20:13.400
[Amit Varma]: political success. But my question here is that the moment as this sort of political

01:20:13.400 --> 01:20:20.320
[Amit Varma]: phase, the imperatives of electoral politics come into play, where you're, you know, as

01:20:20.320 --> 01:20:26.040
[Amit Varma]: a movement, your dharma is to achieve whatever aim you are aiming for, and you can be idealistic.

01:20:26.040 --> 01:20:31.960
[Amit Varma]: As a political party, your dharma is to win votes. And I do see a conflict between this

01:20:31.960 --> 01:20:39.920
[Amit Varma]: because even in terms of how AAP has been governing, I see various instances where it

01:20:39.920 --> 01:20:45.600
[Amit Varma]: has given into the imperative of votes over idealism. Quick examples that come to mind

01:20:45.600 --> 01:20:52.120
[Amit Varma]: is, Vishal Dadlani apologizing for, you know, offending that Jain priest because a Jain

01:20:52.120 --> 01:20:57.200
[Amit Varma]: vote bank mattered to Mr. Kejriwal. Then, for example, opposing FDI in retail because

01:20:57.200 --> 01:21:02.440
[Amit Varma]: part of their vote base is an interest group of small traders. Even recently, they're not

01:21:02.440 --> 01:21:06.960
[Amit Varma]: coming out as strongly as many liberals feel they should have against the abolition of

01:21:06.960 --> 01:21:13.760
[Amit Varma]: 370 and the CAA. And at one level, of course, I totally get the practical argument that

01:21:13.760 --> 01:21:14.760
[Guest]: for them.

01:21:14.760 --> 01:21:21.120
[Guest]: I can give you even more examples, I'm sure. I'll concede the point. But I'll only say

01:21:21.120 --> 01:21:29.800
[Guest]: that what you lose in depth, you gain in breadth. A movement for a certain purpose has clarity

01:21:29.800 --> 01:21:35.960
[Guest]: of that purpose and the self-righteousness to not think about anything else. A political

01:21:35.960 --> 01:21:45.360
[Guest]: party doesn't have that room for self-righteousness. But it has potential to do 10 more things

01:21:45.360 --> 01:21:50.320
[Guest]: out of being in the same space. The movement has limited capacity to do anything more than

01:21:50.320 --> 01:21:52.780
[Guest]: the one purpose for which it's established.

01:21:52.780 --> 01:21:57.960
[Guest]: So now you have to ask yourself, if you're able to build schools for children that can't

01:21:57.960 --> 01:22:03.360
[Guest]: go to school, if you're able to provide healthcare for people who are needlessly ill or dying

01:22:03.360 --> 01:22:07.240
[Guest]: because they didn't have the cost, I mean, they couldn't afford the cost of care, would

01:22:07.240 --> 01:22:13.600
[Guest]: you take that? And I submit only that there is no uniform answer to that. I'm not saying

01:22:13.600 --> 01:22:20.280
[Guest]: that my answer is right or yours is right. If it's less pure, that's less pure. I don't

01:22:20.280 --> 01:22:25.280
[Guest]: think anybody can say it's not less pure. And there's a picture in my mind, I've said

01:22:25.280 --> 01:22:29.600
[Guest]: this in many, many people who heard me speak will sort of remember that there's a picture

01:22:29.600 --> 01:22:33.840
[Guest]: in my mind from an article that, I'm going to say Dilip D'Souza or somebody like that

01:22:33.840 --> 01:22:39.760
[Guest]: wrote many years ago. It's a picture of a child standing next to a garbage bin, one

01:22:39.760 --> 01:22:45.160
[Guest]: of those cement bins that we build all over the country. The bin is overflowing, the child

01:22:45.160 --> 01:22:52.720
[Guest]: is like a girl child, scantily clad, some rags, disheveled hair, clearly not had a bath

01:22:52.720 --> 01:23:01.080
[Guest]: in many days. And the child sort of is seeming to, quote-unquote, eat from that space. Now

01:23:01.080 --> 01:23:07.160
[Guest]: you take that picture and you ask yourself, what should you do? What should you do if

01:23:07.160 --> 01:23:10.640
[Guest]: that's the reality? If you're going along in your car and you start at a traffic light

01:23:10.640 --> 01:23:15.680
[Guest]: and somebody, some child knocks on the door and is begging from you, what should you do?

01:23:15.680 --> 01:23:23.080
[Guest]: The immediate question is, well, maybe you can give her some money. Maybe some people

01:23:23.080 --> 01:23:27.000
[Guest]: would have a different view even of that. Well, you really shouldn't encourage that,

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:31.200
[Guest]: all sorts of things. But I'm saying, leave that. I'm not asking the immediate question.

01:23:31.200 --> 01:23:36.120
[Guest]: What should you do about the fact that a four-year-old child or a five-year-old child is begging

01:23:36.120 --> 01:23:42.440
[Guest]: on the street, is eating from a dumpster? And if the only answer you can give to that

01:23:42.440 --> 01:23:50.880
[Guest]: question is, well, really there's not much I can do, then I think you're missing a lot.

01:23:50.880 --> 01:23:56.480
[Guest]: And if you take the view that if I can't do everything to correct this, then none of it

01:23:56.480 --> 01:24:02.280
[Guest]: is worth doing, then also you're missing a lot. I think the challenge for each one of

01:24:02.280 --> 01:24:13.320
[Guest]: us is to be able to do what we can. Pursue the ideal, but recognize that you can't allow

01:24:13.320 --> 01:24:19.920
[Guest]: the good to become the enemy of the ideal. I don't say this as excusing any of the things

01:24:19.920 --> 01:24:26.080
[Guest]: that I, and I myself publicly disagreed with some of these things that you gave as examples.

01:24:26.080 --> 01:24:32.160
[Guest]: I think that's all right. But I think, in fact, by and large, I think there's far more

01:24:32.160 --> 01:24:36.880
[Guest]: room. Now, apart from any of these spaces, parties coming from citizens' movements, there's

01:24:36.880 --> 01:24:42.760
[Guest]: far more space for disagreement, with one obvious exception. We'll talk about that too.

01:24:42.760 --> 01:24:48.640
[Guest]: And I think the important thing, if you want to maintain the room for dissent, the room

01:24:48.640 --> 01:24:56.160
[Guest]: for disagreement with anybody, is first for you to be committed to doing things yourself

01:24:56.160 --> 01:25:02.160
[Guest]: with or without anybody. Once you have made up your mind that in pursuit of universal

01:25:02.160 --> 01:25:08.080
[Guest]: education or universal care or just the dignity of all people, you are going to do something

01:25:08.080 --> 01:25:15.720
[Guest]: with or without anybody else, then all the things that you do with anyone are potentially

01:25:15.720 --> 01:25:21.520
[Guest]: strength-giving exercises to that. But even if you lost those alliances, you must still

01:25:21.520 --> 01:25:27.120
[Guest]: have the capacity and the willingness to go forward, even if no one else were with you.

01:25:27.120 --> 01:25:34.160
[Guest]: And I think that's when you become really able to dissent. That's when you really become

01:25:34.160 --> 01:25:39.440
[Guest]: able to stay a little more faithful to the ideal, a little closer to the ideal, and not

01:25:39.440 --> 01:25:44.640
[Guest]: compromising for good. But it's fair to say that if you didn't win, you couldn't begin

01:25:44.640 --> 01:25:50.360
[Guest]: to implement an agenda that would help that child. And that's also true. It is not...

01:25:50.360 --> 01:25:56.400
[Guest]: If there is a compromise in that, a compromise that is thrust upon you by society and what

01:25:56.400 --> 01:26:03.360
[Guest]: society has allowed, it is too simplistic in my view to call that a compromise of ideals

01:26:03.360 --> 01:26:10.240
[Guest]: itself. You must recognize that it is a deviation from the ideal. I don't, for a moment, deny

01:26:10.240 --> 01:26:16.280
[Guest]: that. But a deviation from the ideal isn't always a compromise of the ideal itself. You

01:26:16.280 --> 01:26:20.520
[Guest]: continue to accept that the ideal is what it is. You even accept that you're falling

01:26:20.520 --> 01:26:24.880
[Guest]: short of the ideal, but that's not the same as compromise.

01:26:24.880 --> 01:26:29.400
[Amit Varma]: So I completely buy your point that there are trade-offs involved. And by turning from

01:26:29.400 --> 01:26:36.080
[Amit Varma]: a movement into a party, you lose that depth and that purity, but you also gain breadth

01:26:36.080 --> 01:26:40.800
[Amit Varma]: and the ability to actually do some things, which is a reason I buy. But it could also

01:26:40.800 --> 01:26:46.360
[Amit Varma]: be a rationalization. And the other sort of homily that comes up very often in the podcast

01:26:46.360 --> 01:26:51.960
[Amit Varma]: is that politics corrodes character. And the reason for that is the incentives of electoral

01:26:51.960 --> 01:26:57.120
[Amit Varma]: politics that you want vote banks to vote for you, so you have to pander to them. At

01:26:57.120 --> 01:27:01.760
[Amit Varma]: the same time, you need money to fight elections, so you have to pander to interest groups.

01:27:01.760 --> 01:27:07.760
[Amit Varma]: And over a period of time, I really can't think of any example where that hasn't happened.

01:27:07.760 --> 01:27:14.080
[Amit Varma]: But this is an open question, obviously, because I guess you would say AAP is a work in progress,

01:27:14.080 --> 01:27:17.960
[Amit Varma]: but some would argue that what you're saying about space for dissent and openness and so

01:27:17.960 --> 01:27:22.640
[Amit Varma]: on, if you look at what happened to Yogendra Yadav or Prashant Bhushan or other leaders

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:23.640
[Guest]: after them.

01:27:23.640 --> 01:27:29.440
[Guest]: So let's take that. I want to give you a little bit of insight into that. And again, you can

01:27:29.440 --> 01:27:33.440
[Guest]: sort of sense that I'm using this podcast to say a few things or a hint at a few things.

01:27:33.440 --> 01:27:37.960
[Guest]: I'm very happy for you to say all these things.

01:27:37.960 --> 01:27:41.160
[Guest]: No, but here's what I would say. We'll come to Prashant in a minute. But on this question

01:27:41.160 --> 01:27:47.360
[Guest]: of the homilies you referred to, yes, I think that's why it's important to concede that

01:27:47.360 --> 01:27:53.800
[Guest]: you are straying from the ideal. And there is an ideal. And to make the ideal the metric.

01:27:53.800 --> 01:27:58.760
[Guest]: And therefore, say, look, it is what it is. This is a strain from the ideal. But the ideal

01:27:58.760 --> 01:28:03.680
[Guest]: does not change because I strayed from it. I strayed from it. And I think people are

01:28:03.680 --> 01:28:07.040
[Guest]: sensible enough to accept that, number one.

01:28:07.040 --> 01:28:13.560
[Guest]: The second thing is to say that we can stray from the ideal, knowing that we are straying

01:28:13.560 --> 01:28:19.800
[Guest]: from it. But also within that itself, keep constantly looking for ways to get back to

01:28:19.800 --> 01:28:24.480
[Guest]: the ideal. That's all it is. That on a day if you do something because you don't want

01:28:24.480 --> 01:28:30.240
[Guest]: to offend somebody, you want to get their vote on election day, whatever it is. Yeah,

01:28:30.240 --> 01:28:36.120
[Guest]: but it hasn't taken away the ideal. A lot of the straying can be momentary. Just because

01:28:36.120 --> 01:28:40.080
[Guest]: you took a step to the left doesn't mean you can't correct that and come back to the right

01:28:40.080 --> 01:28:45.560
[Guest]: or the other way around. And I think systems need that capacity, resilient capacity to

01:28:45.560 --> 01:28:49.160
[Guest]: keep coming back to what they originally set out to do.

01:28:49.160 --> 01:28:54.640
[Guest]: And you can also do structural things. I favor term limits. I think people who are elected

01:28:54.640 --> 01:29:00.880
[Guest]: to a public office should not serve in that office for more than two terms. If you do

01:29:00.880 --> 01:29:07.200
[Guest]: that, you will automatically create a kind of discipline. This politics corrupts this

01:29:07.200 --> 01:29:11.800
[Guest]: character, blah, blah, blah. You just give the guy a hint that a few years from now you're

01:29:11.800 --> 01:29:15.080
[Guest]: not going to be in this job. Think about what you're going to be doing after that and get

01:29:15.080 --> 01:29:19.160
[Guest]: on with that too in life. I think you can perform better if you have term limits.

01:29:19.160 --> 01:29:23.000
[Amit Varma]: It also, to intersect here, creates an incentive in the opposite direction because given that

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:26.800
[Amit Varma]: we live under a predatory state, it creates an incentive of, oh, I'm only going to be

01:29:26.800 --> 01:29:29.600
[Amit Varma]: in power for two terms. Let me make as much money as I can.

01:29:29.600 --> 01:29:32.520
[Guest]: Correct, correct. That is true. For that, you need other checks and balances as well.

01:29:32.520 --> 01:29:35.720
[Guest]: If this was the only check you imposed on yourself, you would have that problem. The

01:29:35.720 --> 01:29:41.320
[Guest]: main check and balance that the Indian system is missing today is the separation of powers.

01:29:41.320 --> 01:29:47.960
[Guest]: That's really the problem, right? The legislatures don't, for practical purposes, the legislators

01:29:47.960 --> 01:29:56.880
[Guest]: don't exist. To my knowledge, since 1983, at least, there has not been a law proposed

01:29:56.880 --> 01:30:05.400
[Guest]: by the government, but defeated by the lower house of either parliament or any state.

01:30:05.400 --> 01:30:10.360
[Amit Varma]: And one reason for this, of course, is the anti-defection law, which stifles debate.

01:30:10.360 --> 01:30:15.880
[Guest]: Yeah. So essentially, the legislature is not, quote unquote, necessary. I did a little exercise

01:30:15.880 --> 01:30:20.320
[Guest]: some years ago. And the other thing is also that because the legislatures have been reduced

01:30:20.320 --> 01:30:27.480
[Guest]: to this irrelevance in law making, whatever the government proposes passes. So there isn't

01:30:27.480 --> 01:30:30.360
[Guest]: really all this thing that we talk about. Occasionally, there'll be a parliamentary

01:30:30.360 --> 01:30:35.960
[Guest]: debate about this. It's just television. It's showmanship. It makes no difference to the

01:30:35.960 --> 01:30:42.720
[Guest]: vote itself in some way. Unless parties as a whole support this or that bill in coalitions,

01:30:42.720 --> 01:30:49.160
[Guest]: lawmaking has ceased to have too much value. It's more like, you can remember Sushma Swaraj

01:30:49.160 --> 01:30:53.760
[Guest]: speaking in parliament, not because it changed anybody's opinion on how to vote on that thing.

01:30:53.760 --> 01:30:58.520
[Guest]: It's just that she said it and it was oratorically nice and all of those kind of things. But

01:30:58.520 --> 01:31:01.880
[Guest]: it made no difference, fundamentally. Those who voted for something were always going

01:31:01.880 --> 01:31:05.440
[Guest]: to vote for it. Those who voted against it were always going to vote against it. And

01:31:05.440 --> 01:31:10.840
[Guest]: partly because the legislator doesn't have the freedom to vote as he says. So the separation

01:31:10.840 --> 01:31:17.320
[Guest]: of powers is one. And I think the courts have contributed to this a little bit by not clamping

01:31:17.320 --> 01:31:22.000
[Guest]: down on the anti-defection law yet. The anti-defection law really should apply only to confidence

01:31:22.000 --> 01:31:26.800
[Guest]: motions. It's obvious that it should apply only to confidence motions. But party bosses

01:31:26.800 --> 01:31:33.480
[Guest]: wanted to apply to every law, every bill. That's all it is. Even today, there is nothing

01:31:33.480 --> 01:31:39.080
[Guest]: in Lok Satta. And these are the sorts of things that we try. Lok Satta didn't have a whip.

01:31:39.080 --> 01:31:41.840
[Guest]: You could argue that if you don't have many elected representatives, not having a whip

01:31:41.840 --> 01:31:45.920
[Guest]: doesn't really mean anything. But I would like to see the day that Aam Aadmi Party does

01:31:45.920 --> 01:31:51.160
[Guest]: not have a whip. And I think it's important not to have a whip. Because when you don't

01:31:51.160 --> 01:31:55.440
[Guest]: have a whip, I mean, you can have a whip for like one line whips and all that. I don't

01:31:55.440 --> 01:31:59.760
[Guest]: think you should have two line whips and three line whips. We can talk about those later.

01:31:59.760 --> 01:32:05.800
[Guest]: But what I'm really trying to say is that if the parties don't encourage the independence

01:32:05.800 --> 01:32:11.440
[Guest]: of the legislature, then almost anybody can be nominated because you don't really need

01:32:11.440 --> 01:32:16.360
[Guest]: them to do anything more than say press yes when they're asked to press yes and press

01:32:16.360 --> 01:32:17.360
[Amit Varma]: no when they're asked to press yes.

01:32:17.360 --> 01:32:21.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you can literally run government from an Excel sheet once the elections are done.

01:32:21.360 --> 01:32:24.920
[Amit Varma]: And I had an episode on this with Varun Mitra where we discussed the anti-defection law.

01:32:24.920 --> 01:32:29.840
[Guest]: But if you remove the whip, everyone becomes important. And there's a legislative record

01:32:29.840 --> 01:32:34.960
[Guest]: of every legislator as well. And I think therefore, the whip should be removed. The anti-defection

01:32:34.960 --> 01:32:40.400
[Guest]: law, in my view, is unconstitutional. But courts have allowed it to continue in the

01:32:40.400 --> 01:32:47.520
[Guest]: mistaken view that it somehow curbs horse trading. In fact, it has led to an extreme

01:32:47.520 --> 01:32:53.760
[Guest]: form of horse trading. And Karnataka is a sort of a celebrated example of all kinds

01:32:53.760 --> 01:33:00.760
[Guest]: of horses. I mean, frankly, even to call them horses is a little bit of an insult to horses.

01:33:00.760 --> 01:33:06.880
[Guest]: Well, OK, if you put it that way. You know what I'm trying to say, that I think that's

01:33:06.880 --> 01:33:13.960
[Guest]: the problem. Term limits are important. Separation of powers is important. The independence of

01:33:13.960 --> 01:33:20.480
[Guest]: legislators is important. Local courts are important. There are lots of these pieces.

01:33:20.480 --> 01:33:24.760
[Guest]: The regulatory bodies need to be far more autonomous. Sarkar should stop doing things

01:33:24.760 --> 01:33:29.960
[Guest]: that it is also a regulatory law. You can't have a system in which the Sarkar runs some

01:33:29.960 --> 01:33:33.760
[Guest]: banks and it also runs the regulatory banks. The Sarkar runs some schools and it also runs

01:33:33.760 --> 01:33:37.960
[Guest]: the regulatory schools. You just cannot. It just makes no sense. And the courts have also

01:33:37.960 --> 01:33:43.360
[Guest]: been amiss in another thing. Many regulatory institutions, like the Information Commissions,

01:33:43.360 --> 01:33:48.520
[Guest]: for example, or just independent commissions like the Information Commission, are in law.

01:33:48.520 --> 01:33:53.480
[Guest]: It says clearly that a fair number of them have to be from outside Babudham. And it has

01:33:53.480 --> 01:33:58.600
[Guest]: never been done. And yet the courts have looked away from it, except the courts tend to frown

01:33:58.600 --> 01:34:02.800
[Guest]: on a few things that government does. And I'll tell you, I have one overriding criticism

01:34:02.800 --> 01:34:09.880
[Guest]: of the courts. The courts are biased against citizens and biased in favor of governments.

01:34:09.880 --> 01:34:14.720
[Guest]: That is, if you are in court and you are one party and the government is the other party,

01:34:14.720 --> 01:34:23.080
[Guest]: even if the government puts out a blatant lie, the courts are broadly inclined to punt

01:34:23.080 --> 01:34:31.520
[Guest]: that ball, rather than say, call it for what it is. I mean, it is 27 years, 28 getting

01:34:31.520 --> 01:34:38.640
[Guest]: on soon, since the 74th Constitutional Amendment for Urban Decentralization was passed. The

01:34:38.640 --> 01:34:43.760
[Guest]: Metropolitan Planning Committee for Bangalore is notified but has no members. What would

01:34:43.760 --> 01:34:49.800
[Guest]: stop any court from saying, implement the law? But if the government were to go to the

01:34:49.800 --> 01:34:54.040
[Guest]: court and say, we are studying this, we are studying that, it's under consideration, the

01:34:54.040 --> 01:34:59.680
[Guest]: court will say, ha ha, come back in four weeks. You understand? The law is very clear that

01:34:59.680 --> 01:35:03.840
[Guest]: there shall be ward committees in every ward, and the ward committee shall be formed immediately

01:35:03.840 --> 01:35:08.400
[Guest]: after the formation of the council, and that they shall meet every month. Everything is

01:35:08.400 --> 01:35:12.800
[Guest]: clear. It's just not done. But if the court were to pull up the government, the government

01:35:12.800 --> 01:35:17.680
[Guest]: will give some explanation, we are studying this, some combination of these things will

01:35:17.680 --> 01:35:24.880
[Guest]: happen, and the courts will say, in four weeks we'll look at it. The courts ruled very long

01:35:24.880 --> 01:35:31.320
[Guest]: time ago, and in your field you're familiar with this, that news on radio should be permitted.

01:35:31.320 --> 01:35:35.360
[Guest]: The government's position, 20 years after the ruling, is that it is still writing the

01:35:35.360 --> 01:35:42.320
[Guest]: rules for allowing news on radio. The courts have ruled a very long time ago, in the Prakash

01:35:42.320 --> 01:35:47.360
[Guest]: Singh case, that there shall be independent police complaints authorities in every state,

01:35:47.360 --> 01:35:51.520
[Guest]: and the whole slew of police reforms were listed in that case. Most governments have

01:35:51.520 --> 01:35:56.880
[Guest]: not done anything on those things. The courts have taken the view that, ha, ho jayega. They

01:35:56.880 --> 01:36:00.280
[Guest]: first take the view that if the citizens are aggrieved by this, they must come and sort

01:36:00.280 --> 01:36:05.000
[Guest]: of petition the courts to force the government to do it. But apart from punting, if they

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:08.720
[Guest]: do nothing, which citizen is going to believe that the court is going to do anything on

01:36:08.720 --> 01:36:17.440
[Guest]: this thing. So by and large, the courts have allowed themselves to be seen as not sufficiently

01:36:17.440 --> 01:36:23.200
[Guest]: engaged with process-driven reforms. Occasionally there's a question of the constitutional validity

01:36:23.200 --> 01:36:28.320
[Guest]: of this or that. Some important question comes up on which one ruling or the other is given.

01:36:28.320 --> 01:36:36.000
[Guest]: But where governance improvement needs to result from creating a balance between state

01:36:36.000 --> 01:36:44.440
[Guest]: market and society, the courts have had a predilection to favour the Sarkar and therefore

01:36:44.440 --> 01:36:50.000
[Amit Varma]: have come in the way of creating that balance. And I guess the structural reasons for why

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:54.840
[Amit Varma]: this is the case would take up an entirely different episode. So let's kind of stay on

01:36:54.840 --> 01:37:00.240
[Amit Varma]: the subject going back to, you know, the topic of dissent on ARP, where, you know, and my

01:37:00.240 --> 01:37:07.440
[Amit Varma]: sense is that every party will naturally tend to drift towards a centralised version where

01:37:07.440 --> 01:37:12.040
[Amit Varma]: an increasingly smaller and smaller group of people get a grip on power, whether it's

01:37:12.040 --> 01:37:17.600
[Amit Varma]: family in the Congress or whether it's the BJP now led by only two people. And it would

01:37:17.600 --> 01:37:22.600
[Amit Varma]: seem that ARP went through an accelerated version of this with so many other leaders

01:37:22.600 --> 01:37:30.280
[Guest]: of stature being sort of forced to leave. Yes or no? Okay, I'll tell you two things

01:37:30.280 --> 01:37:34.720
[Guest]: that happened. One, immediately after IAC, quote unquote, ended, came the question of

01:37:34.720 --> 01:37:40.400
[Guest]: if you're going into the political space, what should Lok Satna do? Right? And I think

01:37:40.400 --> 01:37:51.160
[Guest]: JP was inclined to the view that there need not be multiple forces trying the same things.

01:37:51.160 --> 01:37:56.760
[Guest]: And that if there's a way to converge them, we must be willing to explore that. So we

01:37:56.760 --> 01:38:02.280
[Guest]: tried, a few of us tried to say, can we converge this thing and say whatever it is, whatever

01:38:02.280 --> 01:38:06.120
[Guest]: brand it is, whatever it is. And you were part of Lok Satna then? Yeah, I was part of

01:38:06.120 --> 01:38:10.960
[Guest]: Lok Satna then. I was kind of, you know, I'm sort of in a peculiar position. I've always

01:38:10.960 --> 01:38:18.120
[Guest]: been sort of part of Lok Satna. Also, I mean, when Apo Swaminarayan invited me to be a member

01:38:18.120 --> 01:38:22.440
[Guest]: of the national executive, I attended the launch of the party. I was probably the only

01:38:22.440 --> 01:38:29.480
[Guest]: non-party person who spoke at the launch. I know them as people, right? A lot of us

01:38:29.480 --> 01:38:34.560
[Guest]: know each other as people. And I think that's really the foundation of it. It's not whether

01:38:34.560 --> 01:38:38.680
[Guest]: you agree, disagree, it's whether you're in this shoe or that shoe. And twice, I sort

01:38:38.680 --> 01:38:45.200
[Guest]: of declined to leave Lok Satna. I mean, until Lok Satna decided to hold as a political party

01:38:45.200 --> 01:38:50.840
[Guest]: and give up its political mission, I said, I mean, it's like, you know, you don't leave

01:38:50.840 --> 01:38:55.640
[Guest]: one of your friends to go join another one. That's all it is. And it's also not necessary

01:38:55.640 --> 01:38:58.880
[Guest]: to leave one of your friends to go join. You can do it transparently. I'm with you. I'm

01:38:58.880 --> 01:39:03.680
[Guest]: with you too, right? And my preference is the two of you come together and do something.

01:39:03.680 --> 01:39:11.080
[Guest]: How did those efforts work out? They did go a fair distance. I think JB was for it. I

01:39:11.080 --> 01:39:16.040
[Guest]: think Arvind was for it. They did meet, they did discuss it. I think broadly, they were

01:39:16.040 --> 01:39:23.000
[Guest]: both for it. And if that moment had come through, I think whatever it was, Lok Satna, Aam Aadmi

01:39:23.000 --> 01:39:28.520
[Guest]: Party would have instantly been in a few other states, especially in the South as well. It

01:39:28.520 --> 01:39:33.920
[Guest]: would have gained from a more distributed leadership. It would have sort of, I think

01:39:33.920 --> 01:39:38.080
[Guest]: the brand building exercise across the country would have benefited tremendously. And, you

01:39:38.080 --> 01:39:45.680
[Guest]: know, JP certainly would have brought a degree of a different kind of personage, if you will,

01:39:45.680 --> 01:39:50.560
[Guest]: to the overall thing. And that's needed even today. And to an extent, one could even argue

01:39:50.560 --> 01:39:55.600
[Guest]: that Yogendra brought some of that personage as well. But you need that. You need distributed

01:39:55.600 --> 01:39:59.400
[Guest]: leadership. You need, especially because ultimately, if you're going to capture power in more than

01:39:59.400 --> 01:40:01.920
[Guest]: one state, you need people to be able to stand up in those states.

01:40:01.920 --> 01:40:05.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it could have, just thinking aloud, could have been a national party today and

01:40:05.120 --> 01:40:06.120
[Amit Varma]: a real alternative.

01:40:06.120 --> 01:40:11.800
[Guest]: Could have, yes. And the only thing I will say is that I don't blame Arvind for it. I

01:40:11.800 --> 01:40:18.040
[Guest]: think he was for it, that he actually understood that it was possible. I'm not going to say

01:40:18.040 --> 01:40:22.480
[Guest]: it's his first instinct or last instinct, but when it was put forward, I don't think

01:40:22.480 --> 01:40:28.240
[Guest]: he stood in the way. But it didn't happen. It didn't happen in any event.

01:40:28.240 --> 01:40:29.760
[Guest]: Why didn't it?

01:40:29.760 --> 01:40:36.320
[Guest]: I don't know this for sure, but I felt Yogendra and Prashant were not for it. I don't know

01:40:36.320 --> 01:40:43.200
[Guest]: this for sure. And perhaps a few other people were not for it as well. And the moment passed.

01:40:43.200 --> 01:40:48.760
[Guest]: And the subsequent thing about what happened with Yogendra and Prashant, I'm not really

01:40:48.760 --> 01:40:54.520
[Guest]: privy to that well enough to be able to comment on that. But clearly, one could see that the

01:40:54.520 --> 01:41:00.280
[Guest]: kind of thing that we spoke about earlier, that whether the good is the enemy or the

01:41:00.280 --> 01:41:07.640
[Guest]: ideal permeated that debate. And perhaps it was a bit of a scimitar to the whole thing

01:41:07.640 --> 01:41:15.160
[Guest]: to say, get on with it. Either you're with me or against me. It was unnecessary. And

01:41:15.160 --> 01:41:20.480
[Guest]: I think the movement did lose as a result.

01:41:20.480 --> 01:41:26.880
[Guest]: One could argue that the pragmatic side was able to at least go forward with its pragmatism.

01:41:26.880 --> 01:41:33.600
[Guest]: But I think the movement did lose. All said and done, I've known Prashant for many years

01:41:33.600 --> 01:41:38.880
[Guest]: and I have a fair amount of regard for the things that he has tried to do. And it would

01:41:38.880 --> 01:41:44.560
[Guest]: have been nice to be able to go forward with him as well. I'm not talking about the party

01:41:44.560 --> 01:41:51.240
[Guest]: itself. The party is sort of an instrument that you create. The purpose is what brings

01:41:51.240 --> 01:41:57.280
[Guest]: people together. And the party is a brand and popularity building exercise for that

01:41:57.280 --> 01:42:03.760
[Guest]: purpose in some way. And I think the fact that people started to go in different directions,

01:42:03.760 --> 01:42:08.560
[Guest]: we did lose as a result of this. And I don't think... The loss to me is not that we lost

01:42:08.560 --> 01:42:12.440
[Guest]: the opportunity to build a national party. The loss to me is that we lost the opportunity

01:42:12.440 --> 01:42:17.680
[Guest]: to accelerate movement towards the goals that you had set for yourself. That's all it is.

01:42:17.680 --> 01:42:21.640
[Guest]: I would be quite happy if Congress or BJP or 20 other parties also did the same thing.

01:42:21.640 --> 01:42:28.480
[Guest]: But I also want to say one other thing. I think during the Rajya Sabha elections in

01:42:28.480 --> 01:42:34.840
[Guest]: Delhi about 18 months ago, something like that. Now, there was an opportunity to bridge

01:42:34.840 --> 01:42:43.640
[Guest]: this. Whatever you call it, bridge this. And that also was tried. But it didn't happen

01:42:43.640 --> 01:42:49.040
[Guest]: again. And again, I give credit to Arvind. He was willing to try that. But it didn't

01:42:49.040 --> 01:42:53.600
[Guest]: happen. It takes two hands to clap. That's all it is.

01:42:53.600 --> 01:42:55.600
[Guest]: What was the opportunity? Sorry, I'm not aware of it.

01:42:55.600 --> 01:42:59.840
[Guest]: Well, the app could dominate three people to the Rajya Sabha in Delhi. And that was

01:42:59.840 --> 01:43:06.040
[Guest]: a good opportunity to say, whatever the differences may have been in the past, can we consider

01:43:06.040 --> 01:43:13.000
[Guest]: a scenario in which we come back together again? And in the process, maybe make one

01:43:13.000 --> 01:43:20.840
[Guest]: of those guys, one of those members as well. And I think that opportunity existed. Arvind

01:43:20.840 --> 01:43:24.920
[Guest]: was not against it. But it didn't happen.

01:43:24.920 --> 01:43:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. So, before we eventually go back to the central theme of this participatory democracy...

01:43:30.000 --> 01:43:36.040
[Guest]: So, the reason I'm saying this is not to sort of park the blame at somebody else's door.

01:43:36.040 --> 01:43:43.720
[Guest]: Because I think even today, even today, and it's not so much about Prashant or about Yogendra,

01:43:43.720 --> 01:43:54.600
[Guest]: any one set of people. Even today, I think there is need to build a broad coalition for

01:43:54.600 --> 01:44:02.040
[Guest]: a public purpose that spans multiple states, that has understanding of the realities of

01:44:02.040 --> 01:44:10.440
[Guest]: multiple states, and is able to function through local leadership and local purpose for those

01:44:10.440 --> 01:44:19.240
[Guest]: goals. It's needed. And if a political brand provides a canvas on which to go and try that,

01:44:19.240 --> 01:44:25.520
[Guest]: that is even today, the best thing to do. Even if there is a way in which the forces

01:44:25.520 --> 01:44:33.040
[Guest]: that converged into the civil society side of India against corruption, those forces

01:44:33.040 --> 01:44:41.520
[Guest]: still have a role to play together in taking governance to the next level. Because I look

01:44:41.520 --> 01:44:46.320
[Guest]: at what has happened in the last five years in Delhi government. And I look at that as

01:44:46.320 --> 01:44:52.040
[Guest]: really demonstrating the public administration can be improved, even within the existing

01:44:52.040 --> 01:44:57.880
[Guest]: scheme of things that focus on public service delivery can help, that rationalization of

01:44:57.880 --> 01:45:02.840
[Guest]: services can help, ease of interacting with government can be, you know, some of those

01:45:02.840 --> 01:45:03.840
[Amit Varma]: kinds of things.

01:45:03.840 --> 01:45:05.840
[Guest]: So, let me segue for that.

01:45:05.840 --> 01:45:11.920
[Guest]: Give me a second. I should have said one other thing earlier. I did an exercise about a year

01:45:11.920 --> 01:45:17.880
[Guest]: ago to say how much were bills being debated in the assembly before they were being passed

01:45:17.880 --> 01:45:25.040
[Guest]: in Delhi assembly. And PRS did some stuff and came back with a set of answers. Then

01:45:25.040 --> 01:45:32.880
[Guest]: I asked them to do it only for the period that Aath had been in power. And the data

01:45:32.880 --> 01:45:36.960
[Guest]: wasn't very different. Fundamentally, most bills are debated for a very short period

01:45:36.960 --> 01:45:43.840
[Guest]: of time. The public doesn't even come to know of these bills before they are passed. And

01:45:43.840 --> 01:45:46.320
[Guest]: coupled with the anti-depression law.

01:45:46.320 --> 01:45:52.560
[Guest]: So I proposed two things that I still think are worth doing in some legislature. Ideally,

01:45:52.560 --> 01:45:57.840
[Guest]: I'd like to see AAP do this, but you know, I'm happy if any political party does. I think

01:45:57.840 --> 01:46:04.240
[Guest]: a bill that is proposed in one session of an assembly should only be passed in the next

01:46:04.240 --> 01:46:11.760
[Guest]: session of the assembly. I mean, there should be a minimum period post the introduction

01:46:11.760 --> 01:46:17.760
[Guest]: of a bill that allows opportunity for the public to come to know about it, to engage

01:46:17.760 --> 01:46:22.800
[Guest]: with their elected representative about it, give input, and only then voting should take

01:46:22.800 --> 01:46:23.800
[Amit Varma]: place.

01:46:23.800 --> 01:46:24.800
[Amit Varma]: That's a great idea.

01:46:24.800 --> 01:46:30.080
[Guest]: That's all. It doesn't require anything more than a pause between introductions. And so

01:46:30.080 --> 01:46:34.560
[Guest]: the simplest pause is to say, you introduce it in this session, unless it's some nationally

01:46:34.560 --> 01:46:41.520
[Guest]: important emergency matter, you vote on it only in the next session. I feel that can

01:46:41.520 --> 01:46:42.520
[Guest]: definitely help.

01:46:42.520 --> 01:46:48.640
[Guest]: The second thing that I propose, which I also hope will come back, and with 66 MLAs, this

01:46:48.640 --> 01:46:56.240
[Guest]: should have been easy. The second thing that I proposed is to say, any group of 10 MLAs

01:46:56.240 --> 01:47:03.240
[Guest]: or 15 MLAs, if you like, including not necessarily your MLAs, any parties, any group of 15 MLAs,

01:47:03.240 --> 01:47:10.040
[Guest]: or let's say any group of 15% of the MLAs of a state assembly or parliament must be

01:47:10.040 --> 01:47:17.560
[Guest]: able to introduce a bill without the speaker rejecting it from being tabled. Any group

01:47:17.560 --> 01:47:23.640
[Guest]: of 15% of legislators must be able to table a bill and demand that the whole house vote

01:47:23.640 --> 01:47:29.560
[Guest]: on it. Then you would be restoring the legislative function. Today, legislators don't introduce

01:47:29.560 --> 01:47:36.520
[Guest]: bills. Legislators only vote on bills introduced by the government. So if these sorts of things

01:47:36.520 --> 01:47:40.480
[Guest]: are tried, and I'm talking about this, this doesn't require any change in the anti-defection

01:47:40.480 --> 01:47:45.560
[Guest]: law. It only requires a different stance in government, any government, whether it's

01:47:45.560 --> 01:47:51.280
[Guest]: Amadni Party or BJP or Congress or any other government, to say these are necessary improvements

01:47:51.280 --> 01:47:52.280
[Guest]: in our politics.

01:47:52.280 --> 01:47:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so before we move back to the subject of government by the people and participatory

01:47:57.600 --> 01:48:01.880
[Amit Varma]: democracy, I want to ask one final question about politics, which is, you know, as our

01:48:01.880 --> 01:48:05.920
[Amit Varma]: mutual friend Varun Mitra is fond of pointing out, there is an Indian politics, what he

01:48:05.920 --> 01:48:11.800
[Amit Varma]: calls an ideological convergence, in the sense that in terms of ideology, even if we use

01:48:11.800 --> 01:48:16.280
[Amit Varma]: a flawed left-right spectrum, which doesn't make sense in the context of India, but even

01:48:16.280 --> 01:48:20.600
[Amit Varma]: within that spectrum, all parties are to the left in economics, that is to say they are

01:48:20.600 --> 01:48:26.280
[Amit Varma]: statist and they are to the right on social issues, that is to say that even if they are

01:48:26.280 --> 01:48:31.960
[Amit Varma]: not actively vowing the Hindu vote, as the BJP and the Congress do, they won't at least

01:48:31.960 --> 01:48:37.920
[Amit Varma]: piss it off, which the Amadni Party has been very careful about. So therefore, is there

01:48:37.920 --> 01:48:44.600
[Amit Varma]: then space for a party as Amadni Party by default seems to have moved towards, to say

01:48:44.600 --> 01:48:49.520
[Amit Varma]: that we shall leave ideology aside and not take positions on ideological issues, but

01:48:49.520 --> 01:48:55.120
[Amit Varma]: we will simply provide good governance. We are the state capacity party. Is that something

01:48:55.120 --> 01:49:01.760
[Amit Varma]: that is then likely to resonate with the people across ideological backgrounds to say ki yeh

01:49:01.760 --> 01:49:07.480
[Amit Varma]: sab toh theek hai, ideology apni jaga hai, but mera Bijli Paani Sarak kaise ho raha hai?

01:49:07.480 --> 01:49:14.080
[Guest]: I think yes and no. And this is the problem with all these sorts of questions. I think

01:49:14.080 --> 01:49:22.640
[Guest]: yes, but there are limits to it. That certain things can only be done by a greater balance

01:49:22.640 --> 01:49:29.880
[Guest]: between state market and society. And that is an ideological position. If you don't have

01:49:29.880 --> 01:49:36.240
[Guest]: a view on that, the question you're asking is, is it possible to efficiently do public

01:49:36.240 --> 01:49:42.440
[Guest]: administration despite whatever view you may have of public administration's role in the

01:49:42.440 --> 01:49:46.600
[Guest]: larger picture? And I think the answer is no. But if you didn't ask the second half

01:49:46.600 --> 01:49:50.960
[Guest]: of the question, the answer could be yes. Yes, you can make public administration better.

01:49:50.960 --> 01:49:57.360
[Guest]: I'll give you an example. You can improve the public schools and maybe even the universities,

01:49:57.360 --> 01:50:03.640
[Guest]: but increasingly there's a sense among employers that school and university are not preparing

01:50:03.640 --> 01:50:09.280
[Guest]: young people for the world of employment and entrepreneurship. And there are even people

01:50:09.280 --> 01:50:12.520
[Guest]: like Muhammad Yunus who are now saying, who really wants to get a job? Most people want

01:50:12.520 --> 01:50:17.040
[Guest]: to be self-employed. So this notion of preparing large masses of people to be employed by others

01:50:17.040 --> 01:50:23.480
[Guest]: is itself a daft idea. So if you take all of those ideas together, you could say that

01:50:23.480 --> 01:50:29.640
[Guest]: among the better off sections of society, there is willingness to consider alternatives

01:50:29.640 --> 01:50:36.720
[Guest]: to traditional ways of empowering yourself for life. And that we are now embarked on

01:50:36.720 --> 01:50:42.040
[Guest]: a journey of pushing the masses into a model that we are ourselves preparing to exit from.

01:50:42.040 --> 01:50:47.280
[Guest]: And a lot of things in society are like that, that essentially people seek empowerment by

01:50:47.280 --> 01:50:54.160
[Guest]: exiting from the model that applies to the majority. But they also argue that that majority

01:50:54.160 --> 01:51:00.200
[Guest]: model is necessary to empower the majority. And I think there's a risk of that. One could

01:51:00.200 --> 01:51:05.280
[Guest]: argue that provisioning public services by paying for them is in fact better than trying

01:51:05.280 --> 01:51:10.720
[Guest]: to provide them yourself. But if you're not going to provision them, should you be working

01:51:10.720 --> 01:51:14.720
[Guest]: harder at providing them? Yes. And you could argue that that's really what Manish and others

01:51:14.720 --> 01:51:20.000
[Guest]: have been doing with the education system in Delhi. But in that process, you don't get

01:51:20.000 --> 01:51:24.560
[Guest]: to ask the question of whether provisioning is better than providing. You're only asking

01:51:24.560 --> 01:51:29.600
[Guest]: the question, can you provide better? And perhaps the answer is yes to that. But it

01:51:29.600 --> 01:51:34.640
[Guest]: doesn't answer the ideological question. It doesn't provide clarity on whether it could

01:51:34.640 --> 01:51:39.040
[Guest]: be faster if you provisioned it. It could be faster if you accepted many more things

01:51:39.040 --> 01:51:45.080
[Guest]: as education. It could be faster if you did away with the chop-up. I'll give you an example.

01:51:45.080 --> 01:51:52.680
[Guest]: I met someone at Rashtrapati Bhawan about, I'm going to say three, four years ago, maybe.

01:51:52.680 --> 01:51:57.640
[Guest]: And it was after some discussion and he came up to me and he said, I'm the new chairman

01:51:57.640 --> 01:52:03.960
[Guest]: of AICTE. And he's a well-regarded gentleman. I later understood that he had done some interesting

01:52:03.960 --> 01:52:09.600
[Guest]: and important work in Pune. And I said, sir, I don't want to get off on the wrong foot

01:52:09.600 --> 01:52:17.760
[Guest]: with you. So, I will sort of tell you, in my opinion, AICTE has outlived its usefulness

01:52:17.760 --> 01:52:24.160
[Guest]: and by and large would be better off if we just shut the thing down. He didn't take offense

01:52:24.160 --> 01:52:29.160
[Guest]: and sort of engaged in a conversation about that. And some things have been done even

01:52:29.160 --> 01:52:36.040
[Guest]: in AICTE and UGC, which are improvements on past things. But fundamentally, we have reached

01:52:36.040 --> 01:52:43.840
[Guest]: the point that even well-meaning people who are willing to look at administrative reform

01:52:43.840 --> 01:52:51.240
[Guest]: may not achieve the acceleration of development that India needs because the scope for that

01:52:51.240 --> 01:52:58.040
[Guest]: kind of acceleration to produce, that kind of work to produce development is itself slow.

01:52:58.040 --> 01:53:04.200
[Guest]: And I talk about this in decentralization terms sometimes. If the center spends money,

01:53:04.200 --> 01:53:10.280
[Guest]: the economy will broadly grow at 4% a year. If some of that money is shifted to the states

01:53:10.280 --> 01:53:14.280
[Guest]: and there's equal sharing between the center and the states, the economy will grow at 6%

01:53:14.280 --> 01:53:18.240
[Guest]: a year. If even more money is pushed down to the municipalities and the panchayats,

01:53:18.240 --> 01:53:24.680
[Guest]: the country will grow at 8% a year. This is my thumb rule for why we need to decentralize

01:53:24.680 --> 01:53:29.600
[Guest]: public expenditure. If we did this with the same monies that are currently available,

01:53:29.600 --> 01:53:34.680
[Guest]: the problem today with the slowdown, in my view, is not that there isn't money, but most

01:53:34.680 --> 01:53:38.640
[Guest]: of the expenditure is happening in layers of government that are slow to spend that

01:53:38.640 --> 01:53:44.320
[Guest]: money. And on the private sector side, we've been giving incentives to people who have

01:53:44.320 --> 01:53:50.000
[Guest]: the ability to park money rather than giving breaks to people who will not park money and

01:53:50.000 --> 01:53:55.040
[Guest]: will actually use it to drive demand. If you give the money to the upper half of the economy,

01:53:55.040 --> 01:53:58.240
[Guest]: they can park the money. They don't really need to do anything with it. If you give the

01:53:58.240 --> 01:54:02.560
[Guest]: same money through GST breaks and other breaks to the lower half of the economy, it drives

01:54:02.560 --> 01:54:08.760
[Guest]: consumption, right? Same thing with public expenditure as an accountable thing. The sarkar

01:54:08.760 --> 01:54:13.680
[Guest]: is already spending on the schools. If the schools are not of good quality, you go and

01:54:13.680 --> 01:54:19.520
[Guest]: spend additional money sending your child to a private school. It's duplication of cost

01:54:19.520 --> 01:54:24.120
[Guest]: and wasteful in some sense. This pure economic sense, it's wasteful. It's money being spent

01:54:24.120 --> 01:54:29.280
[Guest]: twice to achieve an outcome. Whereas if you make the first expenditure work properly,

01:54:29.280 --> 01:54:32.880
[Guest]: suddenly there's a wealth of capital available to do a whole bunch of other things in the

01:54:32.880 --> 01:54:38.400
[Guest]: local economy. So I think we need to think of money and the economy in two ways. We need

01:54:38.400 --> 01:54:43.920
[Guest]: to think of the velocity of money at different levels of public expenditure, and we also

01:54:43.920 --> 01:54:49.120
[Guest]: need to think of the velocity of money in the hands of different people. And I've sort

01:54:49.120 --> 01:54:54.120
[Guest]: of come to the conclusion that monies with local governments and monies with the working

01:54:54.120 --> 01:54:59.760
[Guest]: poor are much more likely to turn the economic situation around rather than all the other

01:54:59.760 --> 01:55:03.600
[Guest]: things that get talked about. You know, you can meet industry experts and ask them what

01:55:03.600 --> 01:55:06.520
[Guest]: should be done. You're not going to get anywhere near the answer.

01:55:06.520 --> 01:55:10.920
[Amit Varma]: That's an absolutely fantastic insight. And I'll go back to the ideological question for

01:55:10.920 --> 01:55:14.880
[Amit Varma]: a brief moment for a two-part question. Part one is that when you talk about correcting

01:55:14.880 --> 01:55:20.320
[Amit Varma]: the balance between state market society, what you essentially mean is because the direction

01:55:20.320 --> 01:55:25.920
[Amit Varma]: that our early leaders set us in tilted that balance too much towards a state with very

01:55:25.920 --> 01:55:30.320
[Amit Varma]: little power for society. Correcting that balance, therefore, means empowering civil

01:55:30.320 --> 01:55:36.720
[Amit Varma]: society, right? And even the private sector, because the state is too much of it. Part

01:55:36.720 --> 01:55:41.560
[Amit Varma]: two then is that ideologically, and this is a two-part thing, and again, two parts within

01:55:41.560 --> 01:55:46.840
[Amit Varma]: the second part, where, you know, not to speak of the ARP specifically, but that illustration

01:55:46.840 --> 01:55:53.080
[Amit Varma]: comes up. And part one is, at a broader philosophical level, once you hold the reins of government,

01:55:53.080 --> 01:55:58.480
[Amit Varma]: aren't your incentives and therefore your inclinations likely to be towards maintaining

01:55:58.480 --> 01:56:03.440
[Amit Varma]: the power of the state or strengthening it? That's part one. And part two is that from

01:56:03.440 --> 01:56:08.880
[Amit Varma]: what I hear, and this is anecdotal, whatever good work ARP may have done in the field of

01:56:08.880 --> 01:56:14.320
[Amit Varma]: public education, they have been very distrustful of private education and their policies are

01:56:14.320 --> 01:56:20.320
[Amit Varma]: harming budget private schools. In some cases, I've heard specific instances of where their

01:56:20.320 --> 01:56:25.440
[Amit Varma]: ideological insistence on fee caps are making specific schools shut down.

01:56:25.440 --> 01:56:30.720
[Guest]: Absolutely. But this is what I said, that when you asked the question about public administration,

01:56:30.720 --> 01:56:38.840
[Guest]: I said there are limits that improving providing can only take you so far. Then you have to

01:56:38.840 --> 01:56:44.920
[Guest]: have a view about provisioning. You understand? Now, provisioning can mean I pay, you deliver,

01:56:44.920 --> 01:56:49.400
[Guest]: or you are anyway delivering and somebody is paying, I don't interfere, but it can be

01:56:49.400 --> 01:56:56.040
[Guest]: anything. But I'm saying that there is a worldview that is required about provisioning. And maybe

01:56:56.040 --> 01:56:59.640
[Guest]: one of the political compulsions is that you have an electorate that comes to you and say,

01:56:59.640 --> 01:57:04.960
[Guest]: this provisioner, or the guy who's doing the providing in the provisioning, discipline

01:57:04.960 --> 01:57:12.080
[Guest]: him. The problem is not actually unmanageable, but it is only manageable with transparent

01:57:12.080 --> 01:57:17.760
[Guest]: data. For example, if you take, let me take any instance, education is a good example.

01:57:17.760 --> 01:57:25.560
[Guest]: If you do the math on what it takes to create a space, construct on it, and deliver reasonable

01:57:25.560 --> 01:57:33.360
[Guest]: quality education to a few hundred students in a single space, you can't come up with

01:57:33.360 --> 01:57:41.120
[Guest]: a number that is less than $50,000 a year or $60,000 a year. You can't. Now, most governments,

01:57:41.120 --> 01:57:46.640
[Guest]: by and large governments don't accept this. The governments think that it can be done

01:57:46.640 --> 01:57:52.960
[Guest]: for $10,000 or $12,000. The RTE compensation rates in most states are in that range. But

01:57:52.960 --> 01:57:58.400
[Guest]: the government's view is we are only spending that much on our own schools. Yeah, but what

01:57:58.400 --> 01:58:03.600
[Guest]: are your schools delivering? And why aren't you spending more? The real question that

01:58:03.600 --> 01:58:07.920
[Guest]: we should ask about public education is, why are we not spending 50? I actually don't want

01:58:07.920 --> 01:58:13.160
[Guest]: to get into the private education question too early either. But I'm saying, why don't

01:58:13.160 --> 01:58:19.960
[Guest]: we spend 60,000 rupees per child in the public education system? First, frankly, any amount

01:58:19.960 --> 01:58:25.600
[Guest]: of excess, quote unquote, charging by anybody will get disciplined by that, number one.

01:58:25.600 --> 01:58:32.080
[Guest]: Second, you have to sort of ensure that your proposal for education reform is not promising

01:58:32.080 --> 01:58:35.840
[Guest]: things in the future that aren't available in the present. Kids need to be educated today.

01:58:35.840 --> 01:58:40.320
[Guest]: That if you create a system that will reform itself in 15 years, you're leaving behind

01:58:40.320 --> 01:58:46.080
[Guest]: a whole generation that needs to be educated as well. My thing is that we are going to

01:58:46.080 --> 01:58:52.800
[Guest]: go through this battle of, because we do not acknowledge the true cost of public goods

01:58:52.800 --> 01:58:57.840
[Guest]: in the public sector, there is a tendency to think that there is overpricing in the

01:58:57.840 --> 01:59:04.480
[Guest]: private sector. But if you delivered quality by spending what is necessary in the public

01:59:04.480 --> 01:59:08.600
[Guest]: sector, you will come to a different understanding of what is going on in the private sector.

01:59:08.600 --> 01:59:13.400
[Amit Varma]: And my other sort of response to that would also be that even if we are to accept that

01:59:13.400 --> 01:59:19.000
[Amit Varma]: the private sector is charging too much, nevertheless, no one is saying that you allow them to operate

01:59:19.000 --> 01:59:23.080
[Amit Varma]: and you shut down entirely. You do what you do in public education, but let the private

01:59:23.080 --> 01:59:28.720
[Amit Varma]: sector also do whatever it does so that parents can choose. And if then parents choose a private

01:59:28.720 --> 01:59:35.200
[Amit Varma]: sector over your public education, which is free, then that itself will be a signal over

01:59:35.200 --> 01:59:36.200
[Guest]: the problem.

01:59:36.200 --> 01:59:43.000
[Guest]: I agree. But the problem is that will take a while before your public education is adequate

01:59:43.000 --> 01:59:47.600
[Guest]: enough to offer a genuine alternative to all the people who currently choose the private

01:59:47.600 --> 01:59:49.520
[Amit Varma]: sector is a 10-year job.

01:59:49.520 --> 01:59:53.880
[Amit Varma]: No, sure. But what I'm saying is what is not a 10-year job, what could be done immediately

01:59:53.880 --> 01:59:57.440
[Amit Varma]: except of course, a political economy won't let it happen immediately, is that you let

01:59:57.440 --> 02:00:02.800
[Amit Varma]: the private sector function without any restraints and empower the parents with choice. If the

02:00:02.800 --> 02:00:06.440
[Amit Varma]: parents nevertheless make that choice that I will spend so much money to send my kid

02:00:06.440 --> 02:00:10.680
[Amit Varma]: to a private school instead of a public school, then that's fair enough. They deserve to at

02:00:10.680 --> 02:00:15.960
[Amit Varma]: least have that choice. By taking that choice away, you are doing a disservice to civil

02:00:15.960 --> 02:00:21.160
[Amit Varma]: society at large. And you know, when I speak for empowering the private sector by just

02:00:21.160 --> 02:00:26.280
[Amit Varma]: allowing them to exist, people often think of it as a binary that no, you want government

02:00:26.280 --> 02:00:29.840
[Amit Varma]: schools to shut down, which is not the case at all. Let the government do whatever it

02:00:29.840 --> 02:00:34.080
[Amit Varma]: is with public schools, but let the private sector operate, but you don't do that.

02:00:34.080 --> 02:00:38.800
[Guest]: Yeah, there is room for that. I think Punjab government is looking at some of this, partly

02:00:38.800 --> 02:00:42.640
[Guest]: because of what they hear from across the border in Pakistan trying this thing in a

02:00:42.640 --> 02:00:47.120
[Guest]: larger scale. There are countries around the world that have experimented with this. Even

02:00:47.120 --> 02:00:52.200
[Guest]: cities in America have experimented with school vouchers and things like that. There is a

02:00:52.200 --> 02:01:00.040
[Guest]: way to allow and create both. But I think it will always be true that the substantial

02:01:00.040 --> 02:01:08.600
[Guest]: responsibility for mass education will be on the state. And that currently, we simply

02:01:08.600 --> 02:01:16.160
[Guest]: do not spend enough per child in any state, including in Delhi. I think there's room to

02:01:16.160 --> 02:01:21.240
[Guest]: spend even more per child to prepare them. I mean, Delhi is way above everybody else.

02:01:21.240 --> 02:01:26.320
[Guest]: But even in Delhi, you'll need to spend more per child to be at globally competitive levels

02:01:26.320 --> 02:01:31.600
[Guest]: of foundations for young people. In other states, it's a disaster. I mean, and there's

02:01:31.600 --> 02:01:38.960
[Guest]: also fudging. I'll give you an example. So if you see the SSLC results or whatever, PUC

02:01:38.960 --> 02:01:44.920
[Guest]: results in Karnataka or in any other state, they'll say 67% past percentage, 70% past

02:01:44.920 --> 02:01:48.520
[Guest]: percentage kind of thing. And then if you look at it, what it really means is there

02:01:48.520 --> 02:01:55.520
[Guest]: also 700,000 kids took the exam and about 450,000 or so passed. But that kind of thing

02:01:55.520 --> 02:02:01.560
[Guest]: doesn't ask the question, how many kids should have taken the exam? How many kids are there?

02:02:01.560 --> 02:02:08.240
[Guest]: Of school-leaving age, who should have taken the exam? And that's another 400,000 to 500,000

02:02:08.240 --> 02:02:15.520
[Guest]: kids. So effectively, the graduation rates in most states for those children who you

02:02:15.520 --> 02:02:20.160
[Guest]: would think of as being traditionally served by the public education system is about 35%.

02:02:20.160 --> 02:02:26.320
[Guest]: So you have a situation where one out of three children is graduating from school and two

02:02:26.320 --> 02:02:33.560
[Guest]: out of three are not. And this is a disaster. Most people don't see the data well enough

02:02:33.560 --> 02:02:39.240
[Guest]: to understand this nuance. And also, we seem to be going on a certain trajectory, which

02:02:39.240 --> 02:02:44.240
[Guest]: is delusional. I'll tell you what the delusion is. The delusion is that without widespread

02:02:44.240 --> 02:02:51.680
[Guest]: access to learning for the majority of the population, you can become a developed nation.

02:02:51.680 --> 02:02:58.120
[Guest]: This is the delusion that's playing out. Somehow, India will become a superpower. And after

02:02:58.120 --> 02:03:03.080
[Guest]: that, we will educate the majority. We've got the sequencing wrong. It is only when

02:03:03.080 --> 02:03:08.400
[Guest]: you educate the majority that you can get anywhere close to being a global power. Ultimately,

02:03:08.400 --> 02:03:15.760
[Guest]: the capacity that a country projects externally has to first exist inside the country. And

02:03:15.760 --> 02:03:21.800
[Guest]: we have not given ourselves enough room for that, enough opportunity for that capacity

02:03:21.800 --> 02:03:28.480
[Guest]: to be the collective capacity of the majority. Too many people are just left behind and therefore

02:03:28.480 --> 02:03:36.400
[Guest]: do not get to levels of learning and productivity and just life-enriching work that we are not

02:03:36.400 --> 02:03:38.720
[Guest]: able to project their capacity externally either.

02:03:38.720 --> 02:03:43.320
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely agreed. That's a good point. And I would just add and say that we should not

02:03:43.320 --> 02:03:47.640
[Amit Varma]: only educate the majority, but we should at least allow the majority to educate itself

02:03:47.640 --> 02:03:54.040
[Guest]: if we are not doing that, which is also not the case for ideological reasons.

02:03:54.040 --> 02:03:59.400
[Guest]: I would say a different view, but the schools are not where I would go and apply this thinking.

02:03:59.400 --> 02:04:08.000
[Guest]: I would first say, get rid of this chapa that is being given by the boards through the schools.

02:04:08.000 --> 02:04:13.760
[Guest]: Let anybody, you have a standardized test, let anybody who takes that standardized test

02:04:13.760 --> 02:04:20.160
[Guest]: be eligible to get the necessary certification. And it is none of your business, whether the

02:04:20.160 --> 02:04:27.240
[Guest]: institution that takes them to that point is a school, organized as a school, or organized

02:04:27.240 --> 02:04:31.240
[Guest]: as a learning center of a different type that works well. And I'll tell you why this is

02:04:31.240 --> 02:04:34.920
[Guest]: important. And this is part of some of the work that I've been doing more recently as

02:04:34.920 --> 02:04:40.640
[Guest]: well. There are certain things. So let's say you wanted to become a violinist, or you wanted

02:04:40.640 --> 02:04:49.480
[Guest]: to become a soccer player or a cricket player. School is fundamentally in the way. The notion

02:04:49.480 --> 02:04:58.960
[Guest]: that school and college is the way to succeed is already not true for large numbers of people,

02:04:58.960 --> 02:05:01.960
[Guest]: even when they go to a good school, because their passion in life has nothing to do with

02:05:01.960 --> 02:05:05.720
[Guest]: learning chemistry and physics. You could argue that physics and chemistry have something

02:05:05.720 --> 02:05:10.200
[Guest]: to add to everybody, but not at the scale at which they're required to learn it if they're

02:05:10.200 --> 02:05:15.000
[Guest]: trying to be a cricketer or a violinist, number one. Second, not all schools teach these things

02:05:15.000 --> 02:05:20.000
[Guest]: well anyway. So now by forcing, in fact, the majority of schools don't teach these things

02:05:20.000 --> 02:05:24.720
[Guest]: well. So now you're taking kids who are looking for some, so even if after you force them

02:05:24.720 --> 02:05:28.400
[Guest]: through the system, you have employees telling you that, well, you may have forced them through

02:05:28.400 --> 02:05:32.520
[Guest]: the system. I don't need to acknowledge that in any way. I remember a conversation with

02:05:32.520 --> 02:05:37.680
[Guest]: someone that I hired a few years ago, in which we were having a meal together and I asked

02:05:37.680 --> 02:05:42.400
[Guest]: him a few questions about him and where he came from, what led to his employment with

02:05:42.400 --> 02:05:46.680
[Guest]: me and all of that. And then at some point he said, so you're asking all these questions

02:05:46.680 --> 02:05:51.360
[Guest]: as though you had not looked at my resume when you hired me. And I said, yeah, that's

02:05:51.360 --> 02:05:56.280
[Guest]: probably true. I didn't look at your resume when I hired you. You wanted a job. I asked

02:05:56.280 --> 02:05:59.360
[Guest]: somebody in the company to check out what you could do and to give you a role that is

02:05:59.360 --> 02:06:04.520
[Guest]: commensurate with what you could do and compensation that is commensurate with what you could do.

02:06:04.520 --> 02:06:09.080
[Guest]: I think everybody deserves a chance. I mean, you have to re-imagine the university. You

02:06:09.080 --> 02:06:15.200
[Guest]: have to say, what if everybody could go to college? You eliminate this entrance exam

02:06:15.200 --> 02:06:20.520
[Guest]: and you say anyone can go to college equivalent learning. Some people may do it in three years.

02:06:20.520 --> 02:06:26.600
[Guest]: Some people may do it in 23 years. That is nobody's business. But I think the real problem

02:06:26.600 --> 02:06:34.480
[Guest]: today in the education system is examination and certification through institutions, right?

02:06:34.480 --> 02:06:39.360
[Guest]: If you remove this examination, so supposing you are in ninth standard today and you wanted

02:06:39.360 --> 02:06:45.120
[Guest]: to go and pursue a career in something that isn't doable in school because school doesn't

02:06:45.120 --> 02:06:50.960
[Guest]: offer that. Let's say you want to be a soccer player or a violinist. Now, if you were to

02:06:50.960 --> 02:06:56.640
[Guest]: say I spent four hours of my day preparing to be bad, your parents and everybody else

02:06:56.640 --> 02:07:02.720
[Guest]: around you have a fundamental worry. Will my child go to college? Great. I think that's

02:07:02.720 --> 02:07:10.200
[Guest]: a silly thing to ask whether a child who is pursuing his passion is going to be allowed

02:07:10.200 --> 02:07:17.560
[Guest]: to go to a learning institution. It defies every meaning of the phrase learning institution.

02:07:17.560 --> 02:07:22.840
[Guest]: You should be able to say that somebody who wants to be a soccer player, we should re-imagine

02:07:22.840 --> 02:07:27.680
[Guest]: the learning institution to teach them the things that matter the most to a soccer player

02:07:27.680 --> 02:07:32.200
[Guest]: and to put a university chap or a high school diploma on top of that if necessary. Once

02:07:32.200 --> 02:07:38.080
[Guest]: you re-imagine what the thing that you call certification is, you'll close the gap. And

02:07:38.080 --> 02:07:43.480
[Guest]: my professor was telling me a few weeks ago that in India, you have the largest gap between

02:07:43.480 --> 02:07:48.280
[Guest]: certification and learning anywhere in the world. But when somebody says I've got this

02:07:48.280 --> 02:07:55.480
[Guest]: degree, I don't think anybody attributes any meaning to that. And if you want to close

02:07:55.480 --> 02:08:02.160
[Guest]: that, you have to actually say people who deliver the outcomes that parents want, that

02:08:02.160 --> 02:08:07.600
[Guest]: children want, but even public systems want. People who deliver the outcomes should have

02:08:07.600 --> 02:08:10.560
[Guest]: with that the authority to put the chapa on that outcome.

02:08:10.560 --> 02:08:15.760
[Amit Varma]: These are very wise words. And it also add that this re-imagining of education as it

02:08:15.760 --> 02:08:21.240
[Amit Varma]: were, which is badly needed, is far more likely to come from society with from hordes of problem

02:08:21.240 --> 02:08:26.560
[Amit Varma]: solving people rather than the ossified state. But let's not go down that rabbit hole of

02:08:26.560 --> 02:08:30.440
[Amit Varma]: education right now. I've had episodes on this, which are linked from the show notes.

02:08:30.440 --> 02:08:36.560
[Amit Varma]: Let's get back to the fundamental subject of this episode, which is participatory democracy

02:08:36.560 --> 02:08:41.480
[Amit Varma]: and government by the people. Like you've also written an article, which we'll link

02:08:41.480 --> 02:08:46.880
[Amit Varma]: to in the show notes on your website, where you talk about how in the past, the conventional

02:08:46.880 --> 02:08:50.760
[Amit Varma]: view of government has been government of the people and for the people. And what is

02:08:50.760 --> 02:08:56.560
[Amit Varma]: now happening, which ties in with your idea of the good Indian who is engaged in actually

02:08:56.560 --> 02:09:00.440
[Amit Varma]: participating is government by the people. Elaborate on what this involves.

02:09:00.440 --> 02:09:06.560
[Guest]: So most people have heard Abraham Lincoln's phrase. I won't say the speech. Most people

02:09:06.560 --> 02:09:11.560
[Guest]: only know the phrase from the closing line of his Gettysburg Address that, you know,

02:09:11.560 --> 02:09:15.840
[Guest]: government of the people, by the people, for the people shall not perish from the face

02:09:15.840 --> 02:09:19.840
[Guest]: of the earth. They haven't heard that last part either very much. But they've heard this

02:09:19.840 --> 02:09:26.440
[Guest]: phrase together, of the people, for the people, by the people. And they have a sense that

02:09:26.440 --> 02:09:33.720
[Guest]: together, all three have something to do with democracy. But very few people have thought

02:09:33.720 --> 02:09:41.960
[Guest]: about what does each part of that mean independently? What does for the people mean? What does of

02:09:41.960 --> 02:09:47.720
[Guest]: the people mean? And most importantly, what does by the people mean? I don't think anybody

02:09:47.720 --> 02:09:53.440
[Guest]: has actually thought about it very much in that way. And I think that's the problem.

02:09:53.440 --> 02:10:00.520
[Guest]: Because if you ask yourself what government by the people is, you might come to some understanding

02:10:00.520 --> 02:10:08.400
[Guest]: of public problem solving, in which you see from the outset, both a right and a responsibility

02:10:08.400 --> 02:10:13.440
[Guest]: for you to be in participatory mode, right? It is really the question of what can you

02:10:13.440 --> 02:10:19.960
[Guest]: yourself do? Can you imagine self-government before government? And most people imagine

02:10:19.960 --> 02:10:24.800
[Guest]: government, but they don't imagine self-government. They go straight away to imagining government.

02:10:24.800 --> 02:10:28.440
[Guest]: What are the things that you can yourself do? And why would you go and ask a government

02:10:28.440 --> 02:10:33.720
[Guest]: to do the things that you can yourself do? If you begin with that, I feel you can go

02:10:33.720 --> 02:10:39.080
[Guest]: a lot further. And it also means that when you can yourself do some things, your ability

02:10:39.080 --> 02:10:46.280
[Guest]: to go and ask an official or an elected representative to do more than that is possible. But if you

02:10:46.280 --> 02:10:50.960
[Guest]: do nothing, then he or she can also do the barest minimum. Because you're doing nothing,

02:10:50.960 --> 02:10:54.880
[Guest]: then even the barest minimum is more than what you are doing. By elevating what you

02:10:54.880 --> 02:11:01.040
[Guest]: do, you force the elected, the paid person to do even more. Because if you can do all

02:11:01.040 --> 02:11:04.920
[Guest]: this with nothing, why should you be paying them? You can put that question front and

02:11:04.920 --> 02:11:05.920
[Guest]: center.

02:11:05.920 --> 02:11:15.200
[Guest]: So I feel there is both a practical and a responsible approach to this whole thing,

02:11:15.200 --> 02:11:20.960
[Guest]: which can elevate the game. And like I told you, it's about velocity. If you want to improve

02:11:20.960 --> 02:11:27.000
[Guest]: 400 public spaces in the city, the fastest way to do it is to get local communities involved.

02:11:27.000 --> 02:11:31.360
[Guest]: If you really want to do things at scale, it's really to get communities involved and

02:11:31.360 --> 02:11:35.880
[Guest]: let them do it. Communities, of course, have the risk of potential discrimination among

02:11:35.880 --> 02:11:42.080
[Guest]: themselves and all of that stuff. And the state must be a guardian of equality. But

02:11:42.080 --> 02:11:46.840
[Guest]: I want to use this opportunity to go back to something else. The freedom movement in

02:11:46.840 --> 02:11:51.720
[Guest]: India, we sort of think of it as the independence movement and the freedom movement. But I think

02:11:51.720 --> 02:11:56.720
[Guest]: a very large part of it, keep in mind the Government of India Act existed in the 1930s.

02:11:56.720 --> 02:12:02.840
[Guest]: A very large part of it was actually about self-rule. And this is important in the Indian

02:12:02.840 --> 02:12:12.640
[Guest]: context. And I'll tell you why. In the Constitution, a lot of things are enshrined really well.

02:12:12.640 --> 02:12:21.160
[Guest]: And the state potentially could be an important guardian of many things enshrined in the Constitution.

02:12:21.160 --> 02:12:27.600
[Guest]: But there is one thing that is not sufficiently enshrined in the Constitution. And that is

02:12:27.600 --> 02:12:35.120
[Guest]: the idea of equality. It's not that the Constitution is meant for unequal persons. Of course, it

02:12:35.120 --> 02:12:42.520
[Guest]: is dispremised on the notion that it's about equality, one person, one vote, non-discrimination.

02:12:42.520 --> 02:12:48.360
[Guest]: All these clauses come from some understanding about equality. But the underlying tenets

02:12:48.360 --> 02:12:53.480
[Guest]: of that equality, what in the American Constitution was ascribed as life, liberty, and the pursuit

02:12:53.480 --> 02:13:00.400
[Guest]: of happiness. Now, if you were to ask the average Indian citizen, what is your view

02:13:00.400 --> 02:13:10.800
[Guest]: of liberty, right? You would get a very odd look, by and large. But the notion that democracy

02:13:10.800 --> 02:13:20.120
[Guest]: is partly for the protection of liberty is not widely understood. And that's partly because

02:13:20.120 --> 02:13:27.920
[Guest]: of how democracy came to India. Democracy came to India by ousting a colonial power

02:13:27.920 --> 02:13:34.200
[Guest]: and replacing that with self-rule. And subsequently, various things have been added to it.

02:13:34.200 --> 02:13:37.720
[Amit Varma]: But the self very quickly defined as a state in this instance.

02:13:37.720 --> 02:13:43.520
[Guest]: Exactly, exactly. Which is why the Police Act is from 1861. And many other laws have

02:13:43.520 --> 02:13:51.960
[Guest]: similar problems. But to come back to what I was saying, whereas in European society,

02:13:51.960 --> 02:13:58.680
[Guest]: maybe even in the Americas and a few other places, not everywhere, the notion that democracy

02:13:58.680 --> 02:14:08.480
[Guest]: is necessary for the protection of people's liberties is much more of a factor. And the

02:14:08.480 --> 02:14:15.080
[Guest]: notion that those liberties, what in the American Constitution is written as inalienable rights,

02:14:15.080 --> 02:14:22.160
[Guest]: the notion that this liberty cannot be constrained even by the state, right, is not there in

02:14:22.160 --> 02:14:29.400
[Guest]: our Constitution. In fact, the Constitution contains many, many instances of things of

02:14:29.400 --> 02:14:35.320
[Guest]: liberties that can be constrained by the state, provided for public order, for maintaining

02:14:35.320 --> 02:14:39.240
[Amit Varma]: harmony between communities, for whatever. Like the First Amendment restrictions on the

02:14:39.240 --> 02:14:44.600
[Guest]: right to free speech, for example. Exactly. So in a sense, because the starting

02:14:44.600 --> 02:14:53.000
[Guest]: point, the starting point itself is imagined as good public administration and legitimate

02:14:53.000 --> 02:15:00.840
[Guest]: public administration. Good and legitimate are the starting points from which the Constitution

02:15:00.840 --> 02:15:08.280
[Guest]: presents itself. And public is presented in a fair way as equal, similar, and all of that

02:15:08.280 --> 02:15:14.440
[Guest]: stuff. But really, this notion of liberty, equality... Well, fraternity may be a different

02:15:14.440 --> 02:15:22.320
[Guest]: thing in our context, but liberty and equality. I think we would benefit from examining the

02:15:22.320 --> 02:15:27.840
[Guest]: relationship between the language of the Constitution, liberty in particular and liberty and equality.

02:15:27.840 --> 02:15:34.800
[Guest]: And that's one part of what I think is a problem. The other is how the Constitution was written.

02:15:34.800 --> 02:15:44.080
[Guest]: At the time of the formation of India, once the British left, there was a necessity that

02:15:44.080 --> 02:15:49.560
[Guest]: various territories run by this prince or that prince, this whatever, various kinds

02:15:49.560 --> 02:15:58.320
[Guest]: of people, needed to be converged together into one national identity and a national

02:15:58.320 --> 02:16:04.360
[Guest]: purpose forged out of that. And if you look at the Constituent Assembly debates, it would

02:16:04.360 --> 02:16:12.120
[Guest]: seem to you that people from the constituent regions were willing to give the center the

02:16:12.120 --> 02:16:19.920
[Guest]: necessary power to achieve this. But once that had been exercised, the return of those

02:16:19.920 --> 02:16:24.720
[Guest]: powers to the constituent federating states didn't happen at all.

02:16:24.720 --> 02:16:30.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I did an episode with a historian, Gyan Prakash, about the emergency based on

02:16:30.240 --> 02:16:34.200
[Amit Varma]: his book, Emergency Chronicles, which recently won the Ram Nath Goenka Award, where his central

02:16:34.200 --> 02:16:39.160
[Amit Varma]: thesis was that, look, Indira Gandhi didn't do anything illegal. All the powers she used

02:16:39.160 --> 02:16:44.520
[Amit Varma]: to call the emergency were actually written into the Constitution, because at the time

02:16:44.520 --> 02:16:49.760
[Amit Varma]: the framers of the Constitution sat in that closed room in Delhi framing the Constitution,

02:16:49.760 --> 02:16:54.960
[Amit Varma]: there was violence erupting across the country, and therefore the instinct to centralize.

02:16:54.960 --> 02:16:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And once you do that, power once given can never be taken away.

02:16:58.000 --> 02:17:05.080
[Guest]: Well, it can, but I'm saying it's very hard. It's hard, but you also need a Thatcherite

02:17:05.080 --> 02:17:11.040
[Guest]: moment or a Reaganite moment. But the person who comes to power, and really, you can see

02:17:11.040 --> 02:17:18.120
[Guest]: even Lakshattara in that way, that the person who comes to power has to come to power with

02:17:18.120 --> 02:17:25.760
[Guest]: partly the agenda of returning power to the people. But if you come to power to merely

02:17:25.760 --> 02:17:32.120
[Guest]: exercise that power, but not to distribute it fairly among state market and society,

02:17:32.120 --> 02:17:36.800
[Guest]: then you'll never give it up. And that's the problem. And the reason you need term limits,

02:17:36.800 --> 02:17:43.640
[Guest]: if you ask me, is that by... Term limits are a way of inviting participation in this power

02:17:43.640 --> 02:17:49.480
[Guest]: dealing exercise from outside of conventional sarkar as well. That's why in countries with

02:17:49.480 --> 02:17:55.480
[Guest]: term limits, a lot of people come into public life from non-traditional political backgrounds.

02:17:55.480 --> 02:18:00.200
[Guest]: And that's what it is. You have to come to power to decentralize. And if you come to

02:18:00.200 --> 02:18:04.320
[Guest]: power to decentralize, you can do a lot of these things. I mean, even... I haven't studied

02:18:04.320 --> 02:18:09.600
[Guest]: this well enough, but you could easily say that a state government, like including the

02:18:09.600 --> 02:18:13.600
[Guest]: one in Delhi, should be able to fund ward committees directly. The ward committees are

02:18:13.600 --> 02:18:20.880
[Guest]: required by law. The fact that they have not been set up by MCD and made operational doesn't

02:18:20.880 --> 02:18:25.440
[Guest]: mean that they should not be funded. I remember a conversation in the State Finance Commission

02:18:25.440 --> 02:18:31.200
[Guest]: in Karnataka. According to the 74th Amendment, there should be a Metropolitan Planning Committee,

02:18:31.200 --> 02:18:36.480
[Guest]: which does most of the planning for the city of Bangalore and even a few other cities.

02:18:36.480 --> 02:18:42.000
[Guest]: The MPC doesn't exist in any meaningful way. And the functions that were allocated by the

02:18:42.000 --> 02:18:47.920
[Guest]: 74th Amendment to the MPC continue to remain substantially with the state government. But

02:18:47.920 --> 02:18:53.160
[Guest]: the State Finance Commission has a responsibility only to assign monies to different levels

02:18:53.160 --> 02:18:58.520
[Guest]: of government. Its job is not to say, because the state government has not created metropolitan

02:18:58.520 --> 02:19:03.680
[Guest]: governance, I'm not going to assign any money to metropolitan governance. So I argued in

02:19:03.680 --> 02:19:08.480
[Guest]: the Finance Commission that you assign the money to metropolitan government anyway. The

02:19:08.480 --> 02:19:14.480
[Guest]: politicians will follow the money and create the necessary MPC for that. What has happened

02:19:14.480 --> 02:19:21.440
[Guest]: is that when one branch of the government does something that is, quote-unquote, incorrect

02:19:21.440 --> 02:19:26.600
[Guest]: in some way, there's a tendency for other branches to align with that incorrect course,

02:19:26.600 --> 02:19:31.560
[Guest]: rather than pull it back. And this is a courtesy they extend each other. And this is why the

02:19:31.560 --> 02:19:33.120
[Guest]: courts are biased against citizens.

02:19:33.120 --> 02:19:37.960
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating. So, you know, you've been trying to push participatory democracy, both at an

02:19:37.960 --> 02:19:43.200
[Amit Varma]: initial level, as a civil activist, and then in politics itself with the Lok Satta Party

02:19:43.200 --> 02:19:47.560
[Amit Varma]: and now with the Aam Aadmi Party. And now you're also, you've been involved for a few

02:19:47.560 --> 02:19:52.600
[Amit Varma]: years with urban governance in Bangalore. Tell me a little bit about that journey in

02:19:52.600 --> 02:19:57.840
[Amit Varma]: the sense that, fine, you've gotten into it with a lot of idealism. But has that been

02:19:57.840 --> 02:20:02.000
[Amit Varma]: tempered or strengthened by the obstacles you face? What are the kind of obstacles you

02:20:02.000 --> 02:20:06.600
[Amit Varma]: face? And have you ever thought of just giving it up and, you know, going back to the sort

02:20:06.600 --> 02:20:09.520
[Amit Varma]: of profit-making sector and, you know, watching stars?

02:20:09.520 --> 02:20:15.040
[Guest]: Yeah, you could do stuff like that. I actually think I have benefited from a certain attitude.

02:20:15.040 --> 02:20:21.840
[Guest]: The things that I want to do in public life for urban governance, or for anything, I don't

02:20:21.840 --> 02:20:28.640
[Guest]: mind if I fail. I don't think I'm defined by that. I think it is necessary to take,

02:20:28.640 --> 02:20:33.400
[Guest]: I'll give you, again, going back to 1905. I like going back to 1905, because a certain

02:20:33.400 --> 02:20:40.720
[Guest]: set of questions were different at that time. Would you say that Gopal Krishna Gokhale failed?

02:20:40.720 --> 02:20:45.960
[Guest]: Because in his time, he did not live to see independence. Now, could you argue that he

02:20:45.960 --> 02:20:55.280
[Guest]: failed? Right? I would not argue that he failed. But I would even argue that he did some things

02:20:55.280 --> 02:21:03.120
[Guest]: that were phenomenally important for subsequent efforts at independence to materialize. And

02:21:03.120 --> 02:21:05.840
[Guest]: he also did one other thing, which I find interesting. He set up one of the earliest

02:21:05.840 --> 02:21:11.040
[Guest]: NGOs in India, and he called it the Servants of India Society. I find both of those things

02:21:11.040 --> 02:21:21.320
[Guest]: fascinating, because I think they are a reminder of a few things. First, that your responsibility,

02:21:21.320 --> 02:21:26.360
[Guest]: I don't want to call it karma, because I don't know that I understand that well enough. But

02:21:26.360 --> 02:21:34.120
[Guest]: your responsibility is to do what you should do in your time and space, because you have

02:21:34.120 --> 02:21:38.800
[Guest]: benefited from what others did in their time and space previously. That's all.

02:21:38.800 --> 02:21:40.080
[Amit Varma]: That's a beautiful thought.

02:21:40.080 --> 02:21:46.000
[Guest]: That's all. I have benefited from the Gokhale's and the Gandhi's and whoever else. And therefore,

02:21:46.000 --> 02:21:54.640
[Guest]: it is contingent on me to do things as well. Number one, you need not succeed. But you

02:21:54.640 --> 02:21:59.240
[Guest]: must try. You need not succeed, you must try. And you should certainly not become married

02:21:59.240 --> 02:22:05.280
[Guest]: to success. You should be willing to say, if I fail, that is not the definition of me.

02:22:05.280 --> 02:22:10.080
[Guest]: But I do many things in life. I pursue many goals. This is one of them. This is an important

02:22:10.080 --> 02:22:16.120
[Guest]: goal for which I should give time and effort. If I succeed, great. If I have to keep trying

02:22:16.120 --> 02:22:24.040
[Guest]: till I can't try anymore, that's also okay. But I think it's not, but you have to do it

02:22:24.040 --> 02:22:31.640
[Guest]: not as indifference to the outcome. You can always say, I mean, it is what it is. I don't

02:22:31.640 --> 02:22:39.000
[Guest]: think it's indifference. I think you should, you know, in a detached sense, see that the

02:22:39.000 --> 02:22:43.280
[Guest]: journey is important, and that you are not that important.

02:22:43.280 --> 02:22:46.840
[Amit Varma]: This is in fact, a lesson I've got from both professional poker, which I played for a few

02:22:46.840 --> 02:22:50.880
[Amit Varma]: years, and the Bhagavad Gita that you can't be results oriented, just do the right thing

02:22:50.880 --> 02:22:56.160
[Amit Varma]: and whatever happens, happens. I've taken a lot of your time and effort for this episode.

02:22:56.160 --> 02:23:02.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'll sort of end by asking, as usual, a two part question, which is that, you know,

02:23:02.520 --> 02:23:08.080
[Amit Varma]: you've lived through and actually been a participant in this momentary shift of what you describe

02:23:08.080 --> 02:23:15.400
[Amit Varma]: as the conception of the good Indian to being someone who is actively engaged in civic affairs

02:23:15.400 --> 02:23:20.880
[Amit Varma]: and in politics and so on. And, you know, one work in progress, which is an example

02:23:20.880 --> 02:23:24.880
[Amit Varma]: of that playing out is the Aam Aadmi Party. But also, I would say that an illustration

02:23:24.880 --> 02:23:30.520
[Amit Varma]: of that is all the movements across the country that have spontaneously sprung up in protest

02:23:30.520 --> 02:23:36.160
[Amit Varma]: against the CIA and so on. There are many, perhaps manifestations where people are involving

02:23:36.160 --> 02:23:43.560
[Amit Varma]: themselves in politics defined broadly. So looking ahead, say for the next 15-20 years,

02:23:43.560 --> 02:23:48.680
[Amit Varma]: what is the best case scenario and the worst case scenario for our great nation?

02:23:48.680 --> 02:23:55.000
[Guest]: The best case scenario is that we embrace both decentralization and federalism. And

02:23:55.000 --> 02:24:01.760
[Guest]: but we do it in a responsible way, not in anger against the center, but in a way that

02:24:01.760 --> 02:24:11.520
[Guest]: recognizes that the center is the collective strength of our federating entities, and that

02:24:11.520 --> 02:24:17.920
[Guest]: it has its own role to play. That's the best case scenario, that we come to that understanding

02:24:17.920 --> 02:24:26.960
[Guest]: as a people, as a population, as a citizenry in some ways. The worst case scenario is that

02:24:26.960 --> 02:24:34.560
[Guest]: we miss that bus. And India is a land of what JP used to call avoidable suffering. You know

02:24:34.560 --> 02:24:35.560
[Guest]: what I mean?

02:24:35.560 --> 02:24:36.560
[Guest]: That's a great phrase.

02:24:36.560 --> 02:24:42.800
[Guest]: Unfortunately, if we do nothing, 15 more million children will go uneducated this year. And

02:24:42.800 --> 02:24:47.400
[Guest]: those numbers are staggering. We live among the largest concentrations of poor people

02:24:47.400 --> 02:24:52.440
[Guest]: in the history of the planet in India. If we do nothing, 15 million people will go without

02:24:52.440 --> 02:24:55.960
[Guest]: education. If we do nothing, six and a half million of them will go without healthcare.

02:24:55.960 --> 02:24:59.920
[Guest]: If we do nothing, all sorts of bad things will happen to very, very large numbers of

02:24:59.920 --> 02:25:04.320
[Guest]: people. 60% of the people who are coming out of poverty tend to fall back into it already.

02:25:04.320 --> 02:25:10.640
[Guest]: If we do nothing, we are already at some of the lowest and high unemployment rates in

02:25:10.640 --> 02:25:16.040
[Guest]: recent times. I feel, I mean, highest unemployment rates in recent times. But what I'm trying

02:25:16.040 --> 02:25:23.360
[Guest]: to say is that the cost of doing nothing to correct course is very, very high. And a lot

02:25:23.360 --> 02:25:29.320
[Guest]: of the things that we see on the streets as anger are really... But CAA is a different

02:25:29.320 --> 02:25:34.360
[Guest]: country. In general, a lot of the anger that we see in protest movements are really fear

02:25:34.360 --> 02:25:39.920
[Guest]: and anxiety about the future among a very large section of the population that feels

02:25:39.920 --> 02:25:45.680
[Guest]: that no one is looking out for them. I think it's important. Gandhiji used to say, and

